[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Introduction"]
[Black "Kalashnikov"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5
{ The Kalashnikov Sicilian is quite similar to the Sveshnikov. The most obvious difference is that here both the b1 and the g8 Knights remain on their starting squares, which entails some changes.   Black has some extra options, like playing …Be7+Bg5 to trade Bishops, pushing …f5 without having to retreat the Knight or even developing this Knight on e7 and the Bishop via …g6+Bg7. Also, the typical Bg5 pin won't be so easy for White.   Obviously, there are some drawbacks as well: since White hasn't been forced to play Nc3, there is the extra option of playing some Maroczy-like setup by means of c4, and that's how we are going to play. }
5. Nb5 d6 6. c4 Be7 7. N5c3
{ Far less known than the absolute main move  7.N1c3  . The key is enjoying more flexibility with our Knights, as we keep the extra option Nd5-Nbc3.   It may look like this move wastes one tempo compared to N1c3.   However, it's very likely that …a6 is going to be played anyway.   Also, as in this position the center is closed, we can comfortably afford this. }
7... Nf6 8. Bd3
{ Here our Bishop guards the e4-pawn, and so Nd5 will be easier in the future. }
8... O-O 9. O-O Nd7
{ The most played move, and also most played among top players. Black intends …Bg5, as well as the …Nc5 regroup. }
10. Nd5
{ Now that the direct capture is not possible, we take advantage to improve our Knights. }
10... Bg5 11. Nbc3
{ Taking on g5 makes no sense, as that would improve the black Queen. We'd rather wait for Black to take on c1, which would improve our Rook. }
11... Nc5 12. b4 Bxc1 13. Rxc1 Ne6 14. Qd2
{ With a very comfortable position thanks to our space advantage and wide choice of available plans. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Introduction"]
[Black "Lowenthal"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 5. Nb5 a6
{ We have reached the initial position of the Lowenthal Sicilian. Black tries to justify all his weaknesses and the pair of Bishops with a quick development.  It is dangerous if we don't know how to play it. }
6. Nd6+ Bxd6 7. Qxd6 Qe7
{ This move is not as popular as  7...Qf6  but lately it is getting a lot of attention. }
8. Qd1
{ It could seem weird to bring the Queen back. However we will see how Black pieces are not in the best squares and that is why we can use this tempo to regroup or pieces. }
8... Nf6 9. Nc3
{ We go on with our development and control the key d5-square. } 9... d6 10.
Bg5 { Pinning the Knight and threatening Nd5. } 10... Be6 11. Nd5
{ Forcing this Sicilian structure, and we will get the pair of Bishops. } 11...
Bxd5 12. exd5 Nb8
{ There are some interesting lines from this moment on.  13.Qf3  is very interesting, trying to castle long.  13.c4  is also a nice line.   However, I am going to recommend  13.a4  since it suits us better to keep the same idea along our Repertoire. }
13. a4
{ Same idea than in other positions, we will push our pawn to a5 and then we will prepare the c5 break. }
13... Nbd7 14. a5 { Now we don't have to worry about our Queenside. } 14... O-O
15. Be2 h6 16. Be3
{ The best square for our Bishop. Aiming directly to c5, helping our pawns to get there. }
16... Nh7 { The only active plan for Black. } 17. O-O f5 18. f3
{ f2 is now available for our Bishop and we are stopping Black pawns in the future. I have added a couple of games to show you how to proceed. }
18... Ng5 19. Ra4 Rac8 20. c3 e4 21. f4 Nh7 22. Bd4 Nhf6 23. c4 Qf7 24. Ra3 Nc5
25. Re3 Kh8 26. h3 Rc7 27. b4 Ncd7 28. g4 Qg6 29. Kh2 Qh7 30. Rg3 Ne8 31. Rg2
Nef6 32. Rfg1 Rg8 33. g5 hxg5 34. Rxg5 Rcc8 35. Qe1 Rc7 36. Qg3 Rcc8 37. Qc3 e3
38. c5 dxc5 39. bxc5
{ 1-0 @@StartBracket@@39@@EndBracket@@ Babic,D @@StartBracket@@2408@@EndBracket@@-Iñiguez,M @@StartBracket@@2318@@EndBracket@@ ICCF 2014 }
*

