1. e4
{ Hello! I hope you are doing great, my name is Miguel Santos and this will be my first video course for Chessable. I have always been an opening enthusiast and I have helped multiple GMs with openings.   I have decided to focus my course on a complete repertoire against the Sicilian. I have been mainly a 1.e4 player all my life and also a 1...c5 vs 1.e4 one, so, I have a lot of experience in the Sicilian.   In fact, the first change I made to my repertoire when I started to dedicate myself professionally to chess was to introduce the Open Sicilian with much more extensive analysis to my repertoire because the vast majority of my games started this way and it was certainly a change that my results were very grateful for.   For this course, I have returned to do the same work looking for new ideas in all the lines that I am going to recommend – logically this course takes quite some time in preparation as it is not easy to find ideas in such specific lines and with such a great theory development.   During that time I have been able to use some of these ideas on the board and they have worked very well for me, so, I am sure that all of you will also find them extremely useful and they will help you to make a quick improvement in chess.   We are going to use the Open Variation against all the Sicilians. In most variations I have chosen strategically correct lines, so that we can understand and play them in the best possible way without requiring an excessive memorization @@StartBracket@@to facilitate this, I have focused on lines that reach similar structures no matter the variation we are seeing@@EndBracket@@.   Obviously, this will not always be so because, when it comes to the Sicilian, as we know, many of these lines end up getting quite long.   The course is full of novelties @@StartBracket@@some of them have already been used in correspondence games or similar@@EndBracket@@ and many others that are 100% novelties, from my point of view @@StartBracket@@and in these times in which everyone has a lot of information to surprise our opponents is increasingly important@@EndBracket@@, and I am sure that with the vast majority of the lines that I have chosen we will achieve that. }
1... c5 2. Nf3
{ In this 1st part of the course we will cover the minor Sicilians and some of the main ones. }
2... Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Qb6
{ The Grivas Variation, a surprise weapon against which we must be well prepared. We will use a very subtle move order that will not allow Black to carry out his plans successfully. }
5. Nb3 e6 6. Nc3 Nf6 7. a3
{ This is my recommendation. A quiet move, but we will gain control for the rest of the game as we will see. }
*

