1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5
{ After this move, we are playing the Pelikan Variation, which according to me, is one of the best two Sicilians, equally good with the Najdorf. }
6. Ndb5 d6
{ The only move to keep a good game. If Black allows Nd6 the position is a mess for them. }
7. Nd5
{ Recently has gained a lot of popularity, all those lines with  7.Bg5  have been overused and White doesn't seem to get any advantage. Apart from this, we will look for the same kind of structure for this and other variations. }
7... Nxd5 8. exd5 Nb8
{ Probably we will find this move more often than any other over the board. This is the most common structure where Black is going to try to have some counterplay on the Kingside and we will try to have our play on the other side of the board. With  9.c4!?  we would get similar positions – it is the variation with most games, however  9.a4  has gained more popularity. }
9. a4
{ The idea of this move is to bring back our Knight to a3 if Black attacks it with …a6. Then we will continue with Nc4 and a5 in the future. }
9... Be7
{ The most flexible move, it is evident, that Bishop was going to move to e7 and Black will castle short. However other moves such as  9...Nd7  ,  9...a6  or  9...f5  have some issues to solve depending on White's move. }
10. Bd2
{ The most precise move order to get the position we are looking for. Also it is less known than 10.Be2, the problem with  10.Be2  is  10...Nd7!  11.Bd2  Nf6!   and if  10.Be2  Nd7!  11.O-O  O-O  11.Bd2  a6  12.Na3  a5!  which is a position we want to avoid with this order. }
10... O-O
{ 11.a5  is also very interesting, however, this move order is more flexible. }
11. Be2 Nd7 12. a5
{ With this precise order we arrive to this position where we have avoided the a6+a5 line. This will help us to bring most of our opponents out of the book while we also get out of the best variation for Black. }
12... a6 13. Na3 Nf6
{ A very interesting idea and concrete which has not been tested over the board. @@StartBracket@@it has been on correspondence@@EndBracket@@. According to engines in depth, Black is very close to equality; however, their position is pretty uncomfortable in practice.  13.c4?!  Ne4!=  . }
14. Bb4 b5
{ 15.axb6!?  Bb7  16.Ba5  Bxd5  17.O-O  Bb7  18.c4  . We have arrived to a complex position where Black has to prove a lot and his pawn on b6 is annoying but I think the text move creates a lot of problems for Black. }
15. c4 Bb7
{ Way better than taking directly, now White is forced to take with the Bishop on c4. }
16. O-O bxc4 17. Bxc4 Rc8 18. b3
{ We have arrived to a very complex position: the weakness on a6 is more evident than the weakness on d5 because takes more effort to defend it. Next step would be to bring the Knight back to e3 and both Rooks to the center. }
