1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5
{ After this move, we are playing the Pelikan Variation, which according to me, is one of the best two Sicilians, equally good with the Najdorf. }
6. Ndb5 d6
{ The only move to keep a good game. If Black allows Nd6 the position is a mess for them. }
7. Nd5
{ Recently has gained a lot of popularity, all those lines with  7.Bg5  have been overused and White doesn't seem to get any advantage. Apart from this, we will look for the same kind of structure for this and other variations. }
7... Nxd5 8. exd5 Ne7
{ 8...Nb4  9.c3  Na6  10.Be3  The knight is very awkward on a6 and White can go on with normal piece development. }
9. c4 Ng6
{ Has been used by Carlsen multiple times in the World Championship, after which it became very popular. }
10. Qa4
{ Very concrete move, we are tickling our opponent. They are forced to play …Bd7 and then we will place our Queen on b4, very annoying for them. }
10... Bd7 11. Qb4 Bf5 12. h4
{ We are trying to chase out that White Knight enabling Bg5 in some positions. if they place their pawn on h5 then they will have some long-term issues without castling because the h5 pawn would be very weak for the rest of the game. }
12... a6 { Well known variation, Black allows h5. } 13. h5 axb5 14. hxg6
{ Very crazy position with a lot of captures and tactics in between. } 14...
bxc4 { 14...Bxg6  15.c5 } 15. gxf7+ Kxf7 16. Qxb7+ Be7 17. Bxc4 h5 18. O-O h4
19. Kh2 { Key move, just in time to play g3 if they play …h3. } *

