[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5
{ The Kalashnikov Variation, it has a lot of similarities with the Pelikan. The most evident difference is the fact that both b1 and g8 Knights are still on their initial position. }
5. Nb5 a6
{ This is the Lowenthal Sicilian. Black is trying to justify all the weaknesses and the pair of Bishops with fast development. It is a very dangerous line if we don't remember what to play. We have to play some moves which are not the most natural at a first glance. }
6. Nd6+ Bxd6 7. Qxd6 Qe7 8. Qd1
{ It could seem weird to bring back the Queen to the initial position. However, we will see how natural it is for White to develop all the pieces while Black has to do some maneuvers. }
8... Nf6 9. Nc3
{ We develop and control the d5 square, which is key in this position. } 9...
d6 10. Bg5 { Pinning the Knight and threatening Nd5. } 10... Be6 11. Nd5
{ Forcing this typical Sicilian structure, however we have both Bishops. }
11... Bxd5 12. exd5 Nb8
{ There are plenty of interesting ideas in this position.  13.Qf3  is very good with the idea of castling Queenside,  13.c4  is also a good standard plan.   However, I will recommend  13.a4  , this move is at least as good as the last two options, but it is very easy to follow with our plan and play with the same kind of structures along the whole Repertoire. }
13. a4
{ Same idea than in similar positions. We will place our pawn on a5 as soon as possible and then we will prepare the break on c5 slowly but consistently. }
13... a5
{ This typical advance to avoid our plan is no longer possible since we already have coordinated our pieces resolutely. }
14. Bb5+ Nbd7 15. Ra3
{ The active Rook is great in this position! We can decide where to move it next depending on Black's reply. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "Kalashnikov #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5
{ The Kalashnikov Variation, it has a lot of similarities with the Pelikan. The most evident difference is the fact that both b1 and g8 Knights are still on their initial position. }
5. Nb5 d6 6. c4 Be7 7. N5c3
{ Less known than the principal  7.N1c3  , our idea is to have enough flexibility with both Knights and we will have the chance to play Nd5-Nbc3.   It could seem like we are losing one tempo by moving our Knight back, however, …a6 is likely to be played anyways and now we have a fixed center, so we won't have any problems. }
7... Nf6 8. Bd3
{ We defend the e4 square which makes it easier for our Knight to jump into d5 in the future. }
8... O-O 9. O-O a6
{ This move doesn't help our opponent too much. However, we must be careful. Nd5 would be a mistake because Black could take with his Knight. }
10. h3
{ Useful move, we gain control over the g4 square and our King has some extra escape. We prepare Be3 and we will wait for Black to play …Be6 and then we will play Nd5. }
10... Re8 11. Be3
{ We keep going with our development and the move …Re8 is not as useful as Be3. }
