1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5
{ The Kalashnikov Variation, it has a lot of similarities with the Pelikan. The most evident difference is the fact that both b1 and g8 Knights are still on their initial position. }
5. Nb5 d6 6. c4 Be7 7. N5c3
{ Less known than the principal  7.N1c3  , our idea is to have enough flexibility with both Knights and we will have the chance to play Nd5-Nbc3.   It could seem like we are losing one tempo by moving our Knight back, however, …a6 is likely to be played anyways and now we have a fixed center, so we won't have any problems. }
7... Nf6 8. Bd3
{ We defend the e4 square which makes it easier for our Knight to jump into d5 in the future. }
8... O-O 9. O-O Nd7
{ This move has been played more times than any other and it has been played by the strongest chess players. Their idea is to prepare …Bg5 while they also want to maneuver their Knight to c5. }
10. Nd5 { Black can't take back so we improve both Knights. } 10... Bg5 11.
Nbc3
{ It doesn't make sense to take on g5 and improve Black's Queen. We will wait for them to take on c1 and we will develop our Rook. }
11... Nc5 12. b4 Bxc1 13. Rxc1 Ne6 14. Qd2
{ With a better position with space advantage and easier plans.   Model Game 1-0 @@StartBracket@@67@@EndBracket@@ Ozols,A @@StartBracket@@2329@@EndBracket@@ -Frijling, J @@StartBracket@@2345@@EndBracket@@ ICCF 2019 }
