[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "Grivas #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Qb6
{ We have reached the initial position of the Grivas Sicilian. Black brings out his Queen prematurely, hitting on the Knight and taking advantage of the Bishop, who can't move to e3. Therefore, our Knight will have to come back to a passive square and later on their Queen could move back to c7. }
5. Nb3
{ After moving our Knight to this square we can attack Black's Queen with Be3. And we will have another piece protecting our King when we castle long. }
5... Nf6 6. Nc3 e6
{ Both Qe2 and Be3 followed by a3 are the most played variations. However in this course I want to give you a different idea to surprise your opponents and objectively it is a very strong move. }
7. a3
{ We will transpose to the main line with  7.Be3  in many lines. However with this move order we will have more flexibility with our plans. }
7... Be7 8. Be3 { We develop with a tempo. } 8... Qc7 9. f4
{ We win space and we prepare the e5 advance. Now the Queen can be developed to f3 without blocking our pawn on f2. }
9... d6
{ Certainly this is the move we will find more often over the board. The problem with this move is that Black has lost flexibility. Breaking the center with …d5 will be more difficult for them with an extra tempo. }
10. g4 { We win space and we will start threatening g5. } 10... a6
{ Very common counterplay from Black with …b5. However our development and space advantage is better. }
11. g5 { We continue to restrict their pieces. } 11... Nd7 12. Qd2 b5
{ Short castle seems crazy for Black because of all our pawns, however White will be able to castle without problems on the Queenside. }
13. O-O-O Rb8 14. Kb1
{ Our King safety is a priority, and the c1 square will be useful for our Bishop in the future. }
14... Nc5 15. f5
{ It is time to strike in the center! Black is losing more and more space, and we will bring all our pieces to the attack. }
*

