[Black "Classical Sicilian #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Nc6
{ Classic Sicilian is without a doubt one of the most difficult openings to understand. One of the advantages is the flexibility, you can play it against 6…e5, 6…e6, or even 6…g6. }
6. Bc4
{ I will recommend one less common move again. Most of your opponents will be prepared for  6.Bg5  , our idea is to get a Be3-Qd2-O-O-O setup and launch a Kingside attack. }
6... Qb6
{ The main alternative to  6...e6  . Black is prepared to play this structure after  7.Nxc6  . And we will play it. }
7. Nxc6
{ The simplest, we reach directly to one of the most typical Sicilian structures where the plans will have more importance than the concrete moves. }
7... bxc6 8. O-O g6 9. Qe1 Qc7
{ This is the trending move today. Black avoids e5 and at the same time sidesteps from the Na4 jump. }
10. Bf4 Nd7 11. Rd1 Bg7 12. b3 O-O 13. Qd2
{ With all those breakups we will follow with Bh6 and we will enjoy our space advantage. }
*

