1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Nc6
{ Classic Sicilian is without a doubt one of the most difficult openings to understand. One of the advantages is the flexibility, you can play it against 6…e5, 6…e6, or even 6…g6. }
6. Bc4
{ I will recommend one less common move again. Most of your opponents will be prepared for  6.Bg5  , our idea is to get a Be3-Qd2-O-O-O setup and launch a Kingside attack. }
6... e6 { Setting up the ordinary structure. } 7. Be3
{ We keep completing our development. Once they have played …e6 there is no more danger of Ng4, that is why we started with Bc4. }
7... a6 8. Qe2 Bd7
{ This is objectively the best order for Black. However a very small percentage of games have been played with this line. }
9. Bb3 { We improve our Bishop position while anticipating for their attack. }
9... b5 10. a3 { Stopping …b4. } 10... Na5 11. f4
{ Very concrete, we keep the posibility to castle on both sides. } 11... Qc7
{ 12.Ba2!?  is very complex after  12...Nc4!  . } 12. Bf2 Be7 13. e5
{ We push that Knight back. } 13... dxe5 14. fxe5 Ng8 15. O-O-O Nh6 16. Rd3
Nxb3+ 17. Nxb3
{ We will double on the d-file. Black's Knight on h6 is out of the game after g4. }
