1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6
{ The Najdorf Sicilian has always been considered one of the best openings. It was played by Kasparov and more recently by MVL, who has fought to show that it holds perfectly. @@StartBracket@@I also play it but that is not relevant for anyone@@EndBracket@@. }
6. Be2
{ My recommendation. I consider this move has a lot of pros compared to the rest of the moves. First of all this move seems harmless. Both natural replies,  6...e5  or  6...e6  could be played here depending on individual preference for any of the structures. }
6... b5 { Black isn't developed enough to justify this. } 7. Nd5
{ We want to trade the only developed piece from our opponent and we prepare to open the position with a4 or c4. }
7... e6 8. Nxf6+ Qxf6 9. Be3 { Followed by c4 or a4. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "Najdorf Sicilian #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6
{ The Najdorf Sicilian has always been considered one of the best openings. It was played by Kasparov and more recently by MVL, who has fought to show that it holds perfectly. @@StartBracket@@I also play it but that is not relevant for anyone@@EndBracket@@. }
6. Be2
{ My recommendation. I consider this move has a lot of pros compared to the rest of the moves. First of all this move seems harmless. Both natural replies,  6...e5  or  6...e6  could be played here depending on individual preference for any of the structures. }
6... Nc6 7. Be3 e5 8. Nb3
{ That Knight shouldn't be played to c6 in this kind of structures. Probably it will be sent back to …Nb8-Nbd7. }
8... Be7
{ It is also possible to play  9.O-O  O-O  10.f3  with a small edge. But as usual, I will recommend a lesser known line. }
9. g4
{ 9.O-O  O-O  10.f3  is possible as well, with a slight advantage, but, as always, I prefer to recommend less-known lines. }
9... h6 10. Nd5 { Our opponent has some problems now. } 10... Nxd5 11. exd5 Na5
12. Nd2 b5 { Only move to keep that Knight safe. } 13. a4 Bd7 14. axb5 axb5 15.
b3 { Punishing that a5-Knight. } 15... Nb7 { 15...O-O  16.Ne4  . } 16. Rxa8
Qxa8 17. O-O O-O 18. Ne4
{ our Knight will keep this great outpost and b5-d6 are targets for the future. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "Najdorf Sicilian #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6
{ The Najdorf Sicilian has always been considered one of the best openings. It was played by Kasparov and more recently by MVL, who has fought to show that it holds perfectly. @@StartBracket@@I also play it but that is not relevant for anyone@@EndBracket@@. }
6. Be2
{ My recommendation. I consider this move has a lot of pros compared to the rest of the moves. First of all this move seems harmless. Both natural replies,  6...e5  or  6...e6  could be played here depending on individual preference for any of the structures. }
6... e5 7. Nb3 Be7 8. Be3 Be6 { The correct move order. } 9. Nd5 Nbd7
{ The most flexible move. } 10. Qd3
{ We develop our Queen and protect the e4 pawn while controlling the f5 square. }
10... Bxd5 { Now we have more options. } 11. exd5 Rc8
{ We must be careful with this move. Black controls c4 and …Nb6 is now a threat. We have to look for a nice move. }
12. c4 O-O 13. O-O Ne8
{ Black is looking to trade Bishops or to play …g6-Ng7. } 14. a4
{ As usual we try to play a5. } 14... f5 15. a5 g6 16. Rfd1
{ We keep bringing our pieces to the center and we leave f1 for the Bishop in the future. }
16... Bg5 17. Qc3 { We prepare Qb4. } 17... Bxe3 18. Qxe3 f4 19. Qf3
{ Just in time to stop everything. } 19... Ng7 20. Nd2 Nf5 21. b4
{ We have shut down everything on the Queen side, now we can focus on how to attack and open more files. }
*

