[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6
{ The Najdorf Sicilian has always been considered one of the best openings. It was played by Kasparov and more recently by MVL, who has fought to show that it holds perfectly. @@StartBracket@@I also play it but that is not relevant for anyone@@EndBracket@@. }
6. Be2
{ My recommendation. I consider this move has a lot of pros compared to the rest of the moves. First of all this move seems harmless. Both natural replies,  6...e5  or  6...e6  could be played here depending on individual preference for any of the structures. }
6... Nbd7
{ Similar line to  6...e6  , we will see that pawn will end on that square in most cases. }
7. Be3 e6 8. g4
{ Again, our idea is to get a common structure, and it is related to this g4-advance. }
8... h6 9. f4 g5
{ Key idea from Black. Everything will depend on the e5 square. } 10. f5
{ Taking  10.fxg5  is OK, however this move adds more pressure on our opponents. }
10... Ne5 11. fxe6 { The most direct attempt. } 11... fxe6
{ 11...Bxe6  12.Nf5 } 12. Nf3
{ Black has several options but the evaluation stays very similar. We will castle very soon and hit with h4 while their King is on e8. }
12... Nf7 { The best move, that Knight defends crucial squares. } 13. h4 gxh4
14. Qd2 { Now we can castle and attack that King on the center. } 14... Nxg4
15. Bd4 Rg8 16. O-O-O
{ Those pawns are overcompensated with our development and initiative. } *

