{ The ideas of this move are to expand ourselves on the Kingside, the possibility of placing our Bishop on the g2-square and attacking with Ne4+g5+Nf6 in case Black castles short. }
12... Bb7 13. Ne4 { Avoiding Black's long castle. } 13... O-O
{ 13...e5  14.Qf5 } 14. g5
{ Our attacking ideas with Nf6 and Rg1 are so strong. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1) Nimzowitsch-Rubinstein"]
[Black "Nimzowitsch-Rubinstein: 5.dxc3 Nc6 6.Bf4 e6 #6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nf6
{ With this move Black plans to provoke the advance of the pawn to e5 to try to create weaknesses. However, we are going to see how with correct play White can get a nice advantage. }
3. e5 Nd5 4. Nc3
{ We have an advantage in development, which is more noticeable if Black takes on c3. We are not worried about the doubled pawns as they will be useful as a shelter for our King and make our development easier. }
4... Nxc3 5. dxc3
{ In general, we are used to seeing pawn captures to the center and not the other way around. However in this particular case it is much better to take with the c-pawn.   This is because it will greatly accelerate the development of White's pieces as well as open the d-file and make the long castling a safer place. }
5... Nc6 6. Bf4
{ The e5-pawn can become a weakness, so, defending it has some sense. Apart from that, we continue developing our Queenside pieces in order to castle long more easily. }
6... e6 7. Nd2
{ 7.Qd2  is the best-known move, that also gives White an advantage. However, the text move creates more concrete problems that, for sure, our opponent will be unaware of. }
7... d5
{ Only move to avoid the incursion of the Knight. However, this move opens the position quite a lot and White will easily take advantage of his edge in development. }
8. exd6 Bxd6 9. Qf3 Bxf4 10. Qxf4
{ With a nice development advantage. Our King will be safe on the Queenside and our Knight will almost irremediably be sitting on d6. Black definitely is in a lot of trouble. }
10... Qd5
{ Attacking our a2-pawn to stop us from castling long. However, the Queen now is in a vulnerable spot. }
11. Nc4 O-O 12. Rd1 { Starting to win tempi on the Queen. } 12... Qh5 13. Be2
e5 14. Qe3 Bg4 15. f3 Be6 16. Qxc5
{ We follow with O-O and we are a healthy pawn up. } *

