[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nf6
{ With this move Black plans to provoke the advance of the pawn to e5 to try to create weaknesses. However, we are going to see how with correct play White can get a nice advantage. }
3. e5 Nd5 4. Nc3
{ We have an advantage in development, which is more noticeable if Black takes on c3. We are not worried about the doubled pawns as they will be useful as a shelter for our King and make our development easier. }
4... Nxc3 5. dxc3
{ In general, we are used to seeing pawn captures to the center and not the other way around. However in this particular case it is much better to take with the c-pawn.   This is because it will greatly accelerate the development of White's pieces as well as open the d-file and make the long castling a safer place. }
5... Nc6 6. Bf4
{ The e5-pawn can become a weakness, so, defending it has some sense. Apart from that, we continue developing our Queenside pieces in order to castle long more easily. }
6... e6 7. Nd2
{ 7.Qd2  is the best-known move, that also gives White an advantage. However, the text move creates more concrete problems that, for sure, our opponent will be unaware of. }
7... d5
{ Only move to avoid the incursion of the Knight. However, this move opens the position quite a lot and White will easily take advantage of his edge in development. }
8. exd6 Bxd6 9. Qf3 Bxf4 10. Qxf4
{ With a nice development advantage. Our King will be safe on the Queenside and our Knight will almost irremediably be sitting on d6. Black definitely is in a lot of trouble. }
10... O-O 11. O-O-O b6 12. Bd3 Bb7
{ After this we get into a long forcing line that gives White a winning advantage. If  12...Qe7?  Qe4  wins.   If  12...Bd7  Nf3  gives White an advantage. The Rook is attacking through a discovery and we quickly get to hit the h7-pawn as well. }
13. Bxh7+
{ After this unexpected sacrifice, all White's pieces become active very quickly. }
13... Kxh7 14. Ne4 Qe7 15. Ng5+ Kg6 16. h4
{ The pawn joins to attack Black's King and, moreover, it defends our Knight. }
16... Rh8 17. h5+ { A pawn sacrifice to open up lines! } 17... Rxh5 18. Rxh5
Kxh5 19. Ne4
{ Isolating Black's King. The line is long and should not be memorized really because the moves are easy to find over the board. However, it is good to know the idea behind it. }
19... Kg6 { If  19...f5  20.Qg3  prepares the mate on the h-file. } 20. Qg3+
Kh7 21. Rh1+ Kg8 22. Qh2
{ It is important to have the d6-square under control for our Knight. That's why the Queen retreats to this square. }
22... f5 { 22...f6  23.Nd6! } 23. Qh7+ Kf7 24. Qh5+ g6 { 24...Kf8  25.Ng5 } 25.
Qh7+ Ke8 26. Nf6+ { Restoring the material balance. } 26... Kd8
{ 26...Qxf6  27.Qxb7  Rd8  28.Qxc6   28...Kf8  29.Qc7+-  Rd7  29.Rh7 } 27. Qxg6
{ And the Rook penetrates inevitably. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1) Nimzowitsch-Rubinstein"]
[Black "Nimzowitsch-Rubinstein: 5.Ne4 d6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nf6
{ With this move Black plans to provoke the advance of the pawn to e5 to try to create weaknesses. However, we are going to see how with correct play White can get a nice advantage. }
3. e5 Nd5 4. Nc3
{ We have an advantage in development, which is more noticeable if Black takes on c3. We are not worried about the doubled pawns as they will be useful as a shelter for our King and make our development easier. }
4... e6 5. Ne4
{ This is a far less-known move than the main  5.Nxd5  and the idea is to control d6 and kick the Knight away to a worse square with c4. It also makes sense to keep pieces on the board to take advantage of the space that the e5-pawn gives us. }
5... d6
{ It seems logical to try to open the position now that White has moved his Knight again. However, there is a concrete line that will leave us with a very comfortable position. }
6. exd6 Bxd6 7. Bb5+ Ke7 8. d4
{ Black's positon is a total mess.  And they can't play  8...Qa5+  9.Qd2  Qxb5  10.Qg5+!  losing the Queen, Rook or Bishop and then the game. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1) Nimzowitsch-Rubinstein"]
[Black "Nimzowitsch-Rubinstein: 5.Ne4 d6 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nf6
{ With this move Black plans to provoke the advance of the pawn to e5 to try to create weaknesses. However, we are going to see how with correct play White can get a nice advantage. }
3. e5 Nd5 4. Nc3
{ We have an advantage in development, which is more noticeable if Black takes on c3. We are not worried about the doubled pawns as they will be useful as a shelter for our King and make our development easier. }
4... e6 5. Ne4
{ This is a far less-known move than the main  5.Nxd5  and the idea is to control d6 and kick the Knight away to a worse square with c4. It also makes sense to keep pieces on the board to take advantage of the space that the e5-pawn gives us. }
5... d6
{ It seems logical to try to open the position now that White has moved his Knight again. However, there is a concrete line that will leave us with a very comfortable position. }
6. exd6 Bxd6 7. Bb5+ Nc6 8. Bxc6+ bxc6 9. Nxd6+ Qxd6
{ After this more or less forced line we have left Black with a very bad pawn structure. His isolated and doubled pawns can be exploited little by little. }
10. O-O O-O 11. Re1
{ It is important to delay …e5 or, at least, to force Black to play …f6 in order to achieve this push. }
11... f6 { 11...c4   11...Re8  12.Ne5  12.Ne5 } 12. d3 e5 13. Nd2
{ We have now a favorable square for our Knight on c4 or e4 and we will follow with b3 later on. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1) Nimzowitsch-Rubinstein"]
[Black "Nimzowitsch-Rubinstein: 5.Ne4 Nc6 6.c4 f5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nf6
{ With this move Black plans to provoke the advance of the pawn to e5 to try to create weaknesses. However, we are going to see how with correct play White can get a nice advantage. }
3. e5 Nd5 4. Nc3
{ We have an advantage in development, which is more noticeable if Black takes on c3. We are not worried about the doubled pawns as they will be useful as a shelter for our King and make our development easier. }
4... e6 5. Ne4
{ This is a far less-known move than the main  5.Nxd5  and the idea is to control d6 and kick the Knight away to a worse square with c4. It also makes sense to keep pieces on the board to take advantage of the space that the e5-pawn gives us. }
5... Nc6 6. c4
{ Kicking the Knight away from the center and gaining some space. Black has many options after this move, but, as we will see, none of them is close to equality. }
6... f5
{ A very typical reaction in this type of position. Black tries to force exf6 for his Knight to have a more useful square. }
7. Nxc5 Bxc5 8. cxd5 exd5 9. d4
{ After all those trades, our pawn structure is fixed while Black's pawns are clearly weaknesses. }
*

