[White "1) Nimzowitsch-Rubinstein"]
[Black "Nimzowitsch-Rubinstein: 5.Ne4 Nc6 6.c4 Nb6 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nf6
{ With this move Black plans to provoke the advance of the pawn to e5 to try to create weaknesses. However, we are going to see how with correct play White can get a nice advantage. }
3. e5 Nd5 4. Nc3
{ We have an advantage in development, which is more noticeable if Black takes on c3. We are not worried about the doubled pawns as they will be useful as a shelter for our King and make our development easier. }
4... e6 5. Ne4
{ This is a far less-known move than the main  5.Nxd5  and the idea is to control d6 and kick the Knight away to a worse square with c4. It also makes sense to keep pieces on the board to take advantage of the space that the e5-pawn gives us. }
5... Nc6 6. c4
{ Kicking the Knight away from the center and gaining some space. Black has many options after this move, but, as we will see, none of them is close to equality. }
6... Nb6
{ This is the most played move by far, and, interestingly, is one of the worst ones. The Knight is not so well-placed here since he will always be overshadowed by the pawn on c4. }
7. d4 cxd4 8. Nd6+ { This is the key move that players usually miss. } 8...
Bxd6 9. exd6 e5
{ If  9...Qf6  10.Bd3  threatening Bg5 and Black's position is very uncomfortable. A priori we could think that Black's position is not bad since he has a well-defended pawn in the center. However, it is totally lost.   Both the Bishop on c8 and the Knight on b6 will never be able to enter the game while White will continue with his development and Black's position will collapse completely. }
10. Bd3 Qf6
{ 10...O-O  11.Bxh7+!!  No Black piece is defending.  Kxh7  12.Ng5  Kg6   12...Kg8  13.Qh5  Qxg5  14.Bxg5  13.h4+-  Black's King will not survive White's harmonious attack. }
11. c5
{ Defending the key d6-pawn with tempo and we continue our development. } 11...
Nd5 12. O-O O-O 13. Be4 Nf4 14. Bxf4 Qxf4 15. Re1
{ Black's position is completely lost due to the delay in development and the strength of the pawn on d6. }
*

