[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1) Nimzowitsch-Rubinstein"]
[Black "Nimzowitsch-Rubinstein: 5.Ne4 f5 6.Nc3 Nc6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nf6
{ With this move Black plans to provoke the advance of the pawn to e5 to try to create weaknesses. However, we are going to see how with correct play White can get a nice advantage. }
3. e5 Nd5 4. Nc3
{ We have an advantage in development, which is more noticeable if Black takes on c3. We are not worried about the doubled pawns as they will be useful as a shelter for our King and make our development easier. }
4... e6 5. Ne4
{ This is a far less-known move than the main  5.Nxd5  and the idea is to control d6 and kick the Knight away to a worse square with c4. It also makes sense to keep pieces on the board to take advantage of the space that the e5-pawn gives us. }
5... f5
{ This is the most played move. However, this move will provoke weaknesses in the long run around the Black King's position, something that we will take advantage of. }
6. Nc3 Nc6 7. Nxd5 { Doubling the pawns and creating more weaknesses. } 7...
exd5 8. d4
{ The f5-pawn is badly misplaced in this position. Not only weakens the a2-g8 diagonal, but also avoids the c8-Bishop to develop to g4 after the natural move …d6. }
8... cxd4 { This only leaves Black with a disastrous structure. } 9. Nxd4 Qb6
{ 9...Qh4  10.Nb5  Bc5  11.Qxd5+- } 10. Nxf5 Qb4+ 11. c3 Qe4+ 12. Ne3
{ Black's Queen looks weird in that position. We will finish our development while kicking it away. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1) Nimzowitsch-Rubinstein"]
[Black "Nimzowitsch-Rubinstein: 5.Ne4 f5 6.Nc3 Nc6 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nf6
{ With this move Black plans to provoke the advance of the pawn to e5 to try to create weaknesses. However, we are going to see how with correct play White can get a nice advantage. }
3. e5 Nd5 4. Nc3
{ We have an advantage in development, which is more noticeable if Black takes on c3. We are not worried about the doubled pawns as they will be useful as a shelter for our King and make our development easier. }
4... e6 5. Ne4
{ This is a far less-known move than the main  5.Nxd5  and the idea is to control d6 and kick the Knight away to a worse square with c4. It also makes sense to keep pieces on the board to take advantage of the space that the e5-pawn gives us. }
5... f5
{ This is the most played move. However, this move will provoke weaknesses in the long run around the Black King's position, something that we will take advantage of. }
6. Nc3 Nc6 7. Nxd5 { Doubling the pawns and creating more weaknesses. } 7...
exd5 8. d4
{ The f5-pawn is badly misplaced in this position. Not only weakens the a2-g8 diagonal, but also avoids the c8-Bishop to develop to g4 after the natural move …d6. }
8... d6
{ 8...c4  9.Bf4  Be7  10.g3  d6  11.Bg2  Lurking at the d5 pawn and using the light squares. }
9. Bf4
{ It is important to continue development as we prepare to castle long. } 9...
cxd4
{ 9...Be6  10.exd6  Bxd6  11.Qe2+-  Pinning the e6-Bishop and the f5-pawn with check.   9...dxe5  10.Nxe5+-  Getting a strong Bishop on e5. }
10. exd6 Bxd6 11. Bxd6 Qxd6 12. Qd2
{ We prepare the long castle first and then we take calmly on d4, after which we will obtain a nice advantage due to the isolated pawn and the weaknesses in Black's position. }
12... O-O 13. O-O-O
{ We will take on d4 next with a nice advantage thanks to Black's weaknesses. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2) Sicilian with 2...b6"]
[Black "Sicilian, 2.Nf3 b6 3.d4 cxd4 4.Nxd4 Bb7 5.Bg5 Bxe4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 b6
{ In this line, Black aims at some quick Queenside development and to play some Hedgehog-like positions. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Bb7
{ 4...a6  5.c4  Transposing to a Hedgehog system where Black has played a very inefficient move order. }
5. Bg5
{ An interesting move order to start driving our opponent crazy. We take advantage of the fact that …Bxe4 is not good and after …a6 we'll transpose to the main line but surprising our opponent. }
5... Bxe4 { The desired mistake! } 6. Nb5
{ Due to Black's lack of development there is no defense against all the threats. }
6... Nf6
{ 6...Qc8  it wouldn't bother us if they attacked the c2-pawn because we can reply  7.Qe2  with greater threats. }
7. Qe2 { Threatening again Nd6+ } 7... e6
{ Here follows a very forcing and winning line.   7...d5  8.N1c3+-  We will castle Queenside, when Black is behind in development and with serious issues. }
8. Bxf6 Qxf6 9. Qxe4 Qxb2 10. Qxa8 Bb4+ 11. c3
{ Black doesn't have enough pieces to pose problems to our King and the material advantage is huge. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2) Sicilian with 2...b6"]
[Black "Sicilian, 2.Nf3 b6 … 6.Nc3 h6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 b6
{ In this line, Black aims at some quick Queenside development and to play some Hedgehog-like positions. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Bb7
{ 4...a6  5.c4  Transposing to a Hedgehog system where Black has played a very inefficient move order. }
5. Bg5
{ An interesting move order to start driving our opponent crazy. We take advantage of the fact that …Bxe4 is not good and after …a6 we'll transpose to the main line but surprising our opponent. }
5... a6 6. Nc3 h6 7. Bh4 Qc7 8. Nd5
{ Here, Nd5 is extremely strong; the difference compared to the normal line is that after Qe5 our Bishop is not hanging. }
8... Qe5 9. Be2
{ Remember they can't grab the pawn because they would lose the Rook on a8. } *

