[White "2) Sicilian with 2...b6"]
[Black "Sicilian, 2.Nf3 b6 … 6.Nc3 Qc7 7.Nd5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 b6
{ In this line, Black aims at some quick Queenside development and to play some Hedgehog-like positions. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Bb7
{ 4...a6  5.c4  Transposing to a Hedgehog system where Black has played a very inefficient move order. }
5. Bg5
{ An interesting move order to start driving our opponent crazy. We take advantage of the fact that …Bxe4 is not good and after …a6 we'll transpose to the main line but surprising our opponent. }
5... a6 6. Nc3 Qc7
{ In his course, Wesley So recommends  7.Nd5  , which offers White a nice edge as well. However, I think  7.Qd2  will pose Black more practical problems, as well as being objectively really strong. }
7. Nd5
{ This is Wesley's recommendation and it offers a nice advantage as well, but I prefer to give an alternative. }
7... Qe5 { 7...Bxd5  8.exd5  e5   8...Qe5  9.Be3  9.dxe6  fxe6  10.Qf3 } 8. Be3
Bxd5 9. exd5 Qxd5 10. Be2
{ See Wesley´s course, this variation is very good for White } *

