[Black "Sicilian, 2.Nf3 b6 … 6.Nc3 Qc7 7.Qd2 Nf6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 b6
{ In this line, Black aims at some quick Queenside development and to play some Hedgehog-like positions. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Bb7
{ 4...a6  5.c4  Transposing to a Hedgehog system where Black has played a very inefficient move order. }
5. Bg5
{ An interesting move order to start driving our opponent crazy. We take advantage of the fact that …Bxe4 is not good and after …a6 we'll transpose to the main line but surprising our opponent. }
5... a6 6. Nc3 Qc7
{ In his course, Wesley So recommends  7.Nd5  , which offers White a nice edge as well. However, I think  7.Qd2  will pose Black more practical problems, as well as being objectively really strong. }
7. Qd2 { Preparing to long castle. } 7... Nf6 8. O-O-O
{ Again it's very risky to take the e4-pawn because Black lacks development and the Black King is stuck in the center. }
8... Nxe4 { Forces the exchange of our c3-Knight. } 9. Nxe4 Bxe4 10. Bf4
{ Relocating our Bishop into a better square. } 10... d6
{ 10...Qb7  11.f3  Bg6  12.h4!  Gaining space and threatening h5.  h6  13.h5  Bh7  14.Bd3±  One pawn is a small price to pay in exchange for a huge development lead. }
11. Qe3 Bg6 { 11...Bb7  12.Bb5++- } 12. Bxd6
{ Opening up lines against the enemy King. } 12... Qxd6 13. Nb5
{ Next we play Nd6 and the subsequent discovery. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2) Sicilian with 2...b6"]
[Black "Sicilian, 2.Nf3 b6 … 6.Nc3 Qc7 7.Qd2 h6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 b6
{ In this line, Black aims at some quick Queenside development and to play some Hedgehog-like positions. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Bb7
{ 4...a6  5.c4  Transposing to a Hedgehog system where Black has played a very inefficient move order. }
5. Bg5
{ An interesting move order to start driving our opponent crazy. We take advantage of the fact that …Bxe4 is not good and after …a6 we'll transpose to the main line but surprising our opponent. }
5... a6 6. Nc3 Qc7
{ In his course, Wesley So recommends  7.Nd5  , which offers White a nice edge as well. However, I think  7.Qd2  will pose Black more practical problems, as well as being objectively really strong. }
7. Qd2 { Preparing to long castle. } 7... h6
{ There is just one game with this move; however, when the engine goes deeper, this is by far its top suggestion.   The idea is that if White plays the standard plan Bh4 and O-O-O, then after …e6, …Nf6 and …Be7 there will be some threats such as …Nxe4 and White's position is not that fine. }
8. Bf4 e5
{ 8...Qdc8  Wasting a new development tempo wouldn't make any sense.  9.Nd5+-  with lead in development. }
9. Bg3
{ White has to insist with the pin.   9...Nf6  10.O-O-O  d6  11.Nf5  Nxe4  12.Nxe4  Bxe4  13.Ne3  . }
9... d6 10. Nf5
{ Here the Knight puts pressure on d6 and g7, and it also gets an excellent route via e3-d5. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2) Sicilian with 2...b6"]
[Black "Sicilian, 2.Nf3 b6 … 6.Nc3 Qc7 7.Qd2 h6 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 b6
{ In this line, Black aims at some quick Queenside development and to play some Hedgehog-like positions. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Bb7
{ 4...a6  5.c4  Transposing to a Hedgehog system where Black has played a very inefficient move order. }
5. Bg5
{ An interesting move order to start driving our opponent crazy. We take advantage of the fact that …Bxe4 is not good and after …a6 we'll transpose to the main line but surprising our opponent. }
5... a6 6. Nc3 Qc7
{ In his course, Wesley So recommends  7.Nd5  , which offers White a nice edge as well. However, I think  7.Qd2  will pose Black more practical problems, as well as being objectively really strong. }
7. Qd2 { Preparing to long castle. } 7... h6
{ There is just one game with this move; however, when the engine goes deeper, this is by far its top suggestion.   The idea is that if White plays the standard plan Bh4 and O-O-O, then after …e6, …Nf6 and …Be7 there will be some threats such as …Nxe4 and White's position is not that fine. }
8. Bf4
{ The most forcing. The only move is  8...e5  and then we'll try to exploit Black's weaknesses. }
8... e5
{ 8...Qc8  Wasting a new development tempo wouldn't make any sense.  9.Nd5+-  with lead in development. }
9. Bg3
{ White has to insist with the pin.   9...Nf6  10.O-O-O  naturally the d4-Knight is untouchable.  d6  . Now they do threaten to take.  11.Nf5  Nxe4  12.Nxe4  Bxe4  13.Ne3  . With a long-term weakness on d6. }
9... g6
{ Again, a non-developing move and not easy to play at all. However, it is important to prevent the d4-Knight from rerouting via the f5-square. }
10. O-O-O h5
{ It's hard to believe that another pawn push is going to be the right move. However, it's not so easy to refute. }
11. Nde2
{ We remove the Knight from d4 to boost the f4 push and leave the d-file to the Queen. }
11... h4
{ It might look like we're blundering a piece, but Black's lack of development takes its toll. }
12. Nd5 Bxd5 13. Qxd5 Bh6+
{ 13...hxg3  14.Qxa8+-  wins the exchange since their advanced pawn is going nowhere.   13...Nc6  just wins a free pawn  14.Bxe5+-  because both Rooks are en prise. }
14. Kb1 Nc6 15. Bxe5
{ And there's no good way to take on e5. We are targeting d7 and the a8-Rook if the Knight takes. }
*

