3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Bb7
{ 4...a6  5.c4  Transposing to a Hedgehog system where Black has played a very inefficient move order. }
5. Bg5
{ An interesting move order to start driving our opponent crazy. We take advantage of the fact that …Bxe4 is not good and after …a6 we'll transpose to the main line but surprising our opponent. }
5... a6 6. Nc3 Qc7
{ In his course, Wesley So recommends  7.Nd5  , which offers White a nice edge as well. However, I think  7.Qd2  will pose Black more practical problems, as well as being objectively really strong. }
7. Qd2 { Preparing to long castle. } 7... h6
{ There is just one game with this move; however, when the engine goes deeper, this is by far its top suggestion.   The idea is that if White plays the standard plan Bh4 and O-O-O, then after …e6, …Nf6 and …Be7 there will be some threats such as …Nxe4 and White's position is not that fine. }
8. Bf4
{ The most forcing. The only move is  8...e5  and then we'll try to exploit Black's weaknesses. }
8... e5
{ 8...Qc8  Wasting a new development tempo wouldn't make any sense.  9.Nd5+-  with lead in development. }
9. Bg3
{ White has to insist with the pin.   9...Nf6  10.O-O-O  naturally the d4-Knight is untouchable.  d6  . Now they do threaten to take.  11.Nf5  Nxe4  12.Nxe4  Bxe4  13.Ne3  . With a long-term weakness on d6. }
9... g6
{ Again, a non-developing move and not easy to play at all. However, it is important to prevent the d4-Knight from rerouting via the f5-square. }
10. O-O-O d6
{ Several sacrifices can be tried, such as Bb5+ or Ndb5.   However, after some analysis I've come to the conclusion that Nb3 requires less memorizing and also offers better positions. }
11. Nb3
{ After this move we reach quite a peculiar Sicilian where Black hardly has any development, whereas we have our Bishop on g3.   Our plan will be to place our Bishop on d3 to guard e4 and play Kb1 and a3, in terms of defensive play, and our attacking plan will be to prepare f4 and then support this push from behind with a Rook. }
11... h5 12. Bh4
{ Controlling f6 to hinder the Black Knight's development and preparing to meet …Bh6 with Bg5. }
12... Bh6 13. Bg5 Bxg5 14. Qxg5
{ The d6-pawn, without the dark-squared Bishop around, becomes a new weakness. }
