[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 b6
{ In this line, Black aims at some quick Queenside development and to play some Hedgehog-like positions. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Bb7
{ 4...a6  5.c4  Transposing to a Hedgehog system where Black has played a very inefficient move order. }
5. Bg5
{ An interesting move order to start driving our opponent crazy. We take advantage of the fact that …Bxe4 is not good and after …a6 we'll transpose to the main line but surprising our opponent. }
5... a6 6. Nc3 Qc7
{ In his course, Wesley So recommends  7.Nd5  , which offers White a nice edge as well. However, I think  7.Qd2  will pose Black more practical problems, as well as being objectively really strong. }
7. Qd2 { Preparing to long castle. } 7... e6 8. O-O-O Bb4 9. Nde2
{ We prevent the doubling of our pawns and improve our control of the d6-square.   This way, Bf4 is already an annoying move which could potentially force Black to play …e5 or allow us to push e5 ourselves. }
9... Nf6 10. f3 b5
{ 10...d6  11.a3!  After …d6 the Bishop can't retreat to e7 and without this Bishop, Black's position collapses. }
11. Kb1 { Improving our King's position, as well as threatening Nxb5. } 11...
Be7 { 11...Nc6  12.Bf4!  Qb6  13.a3 } 12. Bf4
{ 12...Qd8  13.e5  Nd5  14.Nxd5  Bxd5  15.Nc3  Bb7   15...Bb4  16.a3  Bxc3  17.Qxc3±  16.Qe1+- }
12... Qb6 13. e5 Nd5 14. Nxd5 Bxd5 15. Nc3
{ Next we play h4 and Bd3 with a comfortable attack. } *

