7. Qd2 { Preparing to long castle. } 7... e6 8. O-O-O Nf6 9. f3
{ By placing this pawn here we render both Black's Knight and Bishop useless. We can also play g4 in the near future. }
9... Be7 { 9...b5  is not helping for their development  10.Bf4  e5  11.Bg3+- }
10. g4
{ Gaining a bit more space and starting to prepare to retreat the Bishop to push g5 next. }
10... d6 { 10...O-O  11.Bf4  d6  12.g5  Nfd7  13.h4± } 11. Be3
{ Freeing the way for the g-pawn when needed. } 11... b5 12. a3
{ We stop …b5-b4. As you can see, some ideas are recurring. } 12... Nc6 13. g5
Nd7 14. h4
{ A typical Sicilian position where all White's plans have worked out fine. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2) Sicilian with 2...b6"]
[Black "Sicilian, 2.Nf3 b6 … 6.Nc3 Qc7 7.Qd2 e6 #8"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 b6
{ In this line, Black aims at some quick Queenside development and to play some Hedgehog-like positions. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Bb7
{ 4...a6  5.c4  Transposing to a Hedgehog system where Black has played a very inefficient move order. }
5. Bg5
{ An interesting move order to start driving our opponent crazy. We take advantage of the fact that …Bxe4 is not good and after …a6 we'll transpose to the main line but surprising our opponent. }
5... a6 6. Nc3 Qc7
{ In his course, Wesley So recommends  7.Nd5  , which offers White a nice edge as well. However, I think  7.Qd2  will pose Black more practical problems, as well as being objectively really strong. }
7. Qd2 { Preparing to long castle. } 7... e6 8. O-O-O Nf6 9. f3
{ By placing this pawn here we render both Black's Knight and Bishop useless. We can also play g4 in the near future. }
9... Nc6 10. Nf5
{ Here come the fireworks. Again the Black King, stuck in the center, really suffers. }
10... b5 { 10...exf5  11.Bxf6  gxf6  12.Nd5  Qe5  13.Nxf6  Ke7  14.Nxd7+- } 11.
Nd6+ Qxd6 12. Qxd6 Bxd6 13. Rxd6
{ With the Bishop pair and having provoked all those dark-squared weaknesses in Black's position. }
*

