[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 d5
{ A dangerous line if we don't know it. However, it loses a lot of its value once we are sure how to deal with it. }
5. exd5
{ Forcing the Queen to the center in order to win some tempi on it later on. }
5... Qxd5 6. Be3 { We just develop and prepare the tempo-winning Nc3. } 6...
Nf6
{ This doesn't stop the tempo-winning Nc3 and gives us an excellent position.   6...e5  7.Nc3  Bb4  8.Nb5+-  Too many weaknesses and too little development – Black's position doesn't hold. }
7. Nc3 Qa5 8. Bb5 { We develop and pose threats. } 8... Bd7 9. Qf3
{ Again, the same concept: we are one move away from castling and finally connecting our Rooks, while Black still needs too many moves. }
9... Nxd4
{ This move leads to a forcing line we need to remember.   9...Rc8  10.O-O-O  with an overwhelming development lead. }
10. Bxd4 Bxb5
{ 10...O-O-O  11.Bxd7  Rxd7  12.O-O-O  with a lead in development. } 11. Qxb7
Rd8 12. Qxb5+ Qxb5 13. Nxb5 { And we are on time to protect the Bishop. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3) Sicilian with 2...Nc6 and 4.d5"]
[Black "Sicilian, 2.Nf3 Nc6 … 8.Qd6 Qa5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 d5
{ A dangerous line if we don't know it. However, it loses a lot of its value once we are sure how to deal with it. }
5. exd5
{ Forcing the Queen to the center in order to win some tempi on it later on. }
5... Qxd5 6. Be3 { We just develop and prepare the tempo-winning Nc3. } 6... e6
{ Having …Bb4 available is important to avoid losing more development tempi.   6...Nxd4  7.Nc3!  developing with tempo!  Nf3  8.Qxf3!  without compromising our structure  Qxf3  9.gxf3+-  . }
7. Nc3 { A development and tempo-winning move. } 7... Bb4 8. Qd3
{ 8.Qg4  is the known alternative, which also offers a nice advantage. However, there are not so many games with Qd3 and is even a bit stronger.   We are preparing long castle and preventing the doubling of pawns. We place the Queen on d3 and not Qd2 so that we can unpin when castling long. }
8... Qa5
{ Black's lack of development means they can't afford this kind of moves.   8...Bxc3?  9.Qxc3+-  we would get the dark squares for free, as well as get to exchange one of Black's few developed pieces. }
9. Nxc6 Bxc3+ 10. Qxc3 Qxc3+ 11. bxc3 bxc6 12. O-O-O
{ Our Bishop pair, together with our development lead, is too much for Black. Despite our doubled pawns, we have a huge advantage. }
*

