{ This move is not as popular as  7...Qf6  but lately it is getting a lot of attention. }
8. Qd1
{ It could seem weird to bring the Queen back. However we will see how Black pieces are not in the best squares and that is why we can use this tempo to regroup or pieces. }
8... Nf6 9. Nc3
{ We go on with our development and control the key d5-square. } 9... Nd4
{ Very conrcrete try, it has been played by some GMs. White has to be very precise and we will get a nice advantage. }
10. Be3
{ The most natural move, that Knight is the most active piece for Black. }
10... O-O 11. Bxd4 d5
{ This is they idea behind Black's move order. Lets bring some magic to the board. }
12. Bb6 { The only available square with no threats. } 12... Qb4 13. Bc7
{ This is the idea behind our last move. Black has to justify their sacrifice somehow. }
13... d4 { The only decent try by Black. } 14. f3 Qc5
{ 14...dxc3  15.b3+-  Despite Black's lead in development, the weaknesses in their position yield it totally lost, for Qd6 is a threat that reaches a won endgame. }
15. Bxe5
{ With important threats on the long diagonal, so they have to take or else their Kingside will get weakened. }
15... Qxe5 16. Ne2
{ Until this moment, almost all those moves have been forcing moves, so it is very important to remember them. }
16... Rd8 17. Qd2 { Stepping away from our King's way to his castle. } 17...
Be6 18. Nf4
{ Improving our Knight into the center, and next we will long castle. } *

