Qxf5+ Kg8 23. Nxe4
{ everything is protected, and g6 is coming with deadly results. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "7) Grivas with 9...O-O"]
[Black "Grivas with 10...d6 #23"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Qb6
{ After this move, we have reached the starting position of the Grivas Sicilian. Black's Queen is prematurely developed, hitting the Knight and using the fact that Be3 is not yet possible.   This way, the white Knight will have to move to a rather passive square. Later, the Queen usually drops back to the c7-square. }
5. Nb3
{ This Knight retreat allows us to chase the Queen away from b6 eventually by means of Be3 without having to worry about the b2-pawn.   We'll also have another piece near our King when we castle long. }
5... Nf6 6. Nc3 e6 7. a3
{ Both Qe2 and Be3 followed by a3 are most often played. However, in this course I wanted to give you an idea to surprise your opponents.  Of course, it will be objectively very strong!  In many lines we are going to transpose to the most common variation with  7.Be3  . However, this move order offers us more flexibility. }
7... Be7 8. Be3 { Developing with a tempo. } 8... Qc7 9. f4
{ Gaining space and setting up the e5-push. We also allow our Queen to come to the f3-square without blocking the f2-pawn. }
9... O-O
{ Not a easy move to find if our opponent doesn't know it beforehand, since it involves a pawn sacrifice after the move e4-e5.  That is not, however, White's most accurate follow-up.  10.e5?!  Nd5  11.Nxd5  exd5  12.Qxd5  d6⇆   10.g4?!  d5!   The key. Now Black is actually ready for this break. }
10. Qf3 d6 11. O-O-O { 11.g4?!  d5!  . } 11... a6
{ Black's only way to create counterplay. } 12. g4
{ White has to be active. It's important to dislodge the f6-Knight to make Black's King more vulnerable. }
12... b5 13. g5 Nd7 14. Kb1
{ From now on, both sides have plenty of options. This position is favorable to White, as our attack comes faster and our pieces are better placed to multitask. I recommend these standard plans:   1. Attack: A Rook lift with Rh3-Rg3, keep an eye on the f5-push, keep in mind a chance to push the h-pawn to seek some breakthroughs.   2. Defense: With our Rook on g3 and a Bishop on c1 we'll have most key squares well covered.   Moreover, the Queen on f2 will guard c2 to support eventual sacrifices on that square. Rerouting the Knight from b3 to b5 once Black plays the …b4-break and then pushes the a-pawn. }
14... b4 15. axb4 Nxb4 16. Rg1
{ The Rook is hinting threats to the King on g8. We have other ideas like f5+f6, and then the Rook can swing to h3 via g3.   There it will guard the 3rd rank once our Bishop drops to c1 and then all our pieces will be perfectly coordinated both in attack and defense. }
16... Bb7 17. Rg3 Rfb8
{ With the Rook on b8, Black usually has some …Nxc2 ideas, so we remove our Knight from b3.   On d4 it protects c2 and puts pressure on e6, and it can also jump to b5 in case of ...e5. Black's move also introduces the defensive resource …Nf8. }
18. Nd4 Nc5 19. f5
{ As you can see, this is a complete mess. Curiously enough, Black's own pieces are hampering each other and White's attack is just much faster. }
19... exf5
{ 19...e5  20.g6!  Nxe4  21.gxf7  Kxf7  22.Qh5  Kg8  23.Rxg7  Kxg7  24.Ne6++- }
20. Bc4 { Using the newly-weakened diagonal. } 20... Na4
{ An interesting trick that doesn't work tactically. } 21. Bxf7+ Kxf7 22. Qxf5+
Ke8 23. Nxa4
{ Black's pieces are very passive now and we will continue our attack confidently. }
*

