[White "8) Grivas secondary lines"]
[Black "Grivas, 4.Nxd4 Qb6 5.Nb3 g6 6.Be3 Qb4+ #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Qb6
{ After this move, we have reached the starting position of the Grivas Sicilian. Black's Queen is prematurely developed, hitting the Knight and using the fact that Be3 is not yet possible.   This way, the white Knight will have to move to a rather passive square. Later, the Queen usually drops back to the c7-square. }
5. Nb3
{ This Knight retreat allows us to chase the Queen away from b6 eventually by means of Be3 without having to worry about the b2-pawn.   We'll also have another piece near our King when we castle long. }
5... g6
{ 6.c4  Bg7  would be a direct transposition to a Maroczy Bind against the Accelerated Dragon. }
6. Be3 { Winning a tempo on the Queen. } 6... Qb4+ 7. Nc3
{ 7.N1d2  Bg7  8.c3  Qd6  9.Be2  and White is better; an alternative if we don't want to sacrifice the pawn. }
7... Bg7
{ After this move we have two options:  8.Qd3  is solid and leads to a favorable endgame, and  8.Qd2  sacrifices a pawn to get a complex position with some compensation. Both offer White an advantage and it's all about the type of position we prefer. }
8. Qd2
{ We sacrifice a pawn to get lots of development tempi, the Bishop pair and dark-square control. }
8... Bxc3 9. bxc3 Qxe4 10. c4 d6
{ 10...Nf6  11.O-O-O±  A very complex position, but thanks to our development lead, the dark squares and the tempi we'll win on the black Queen, there is more than enough compensation for the pawn. }
11. O-O-O Nf6 12. f3 Qf5 13. c5
{ The dark squares have been really weakened, as the Black King will be. Therefore, we keep on trying to open up the position. }
*

