[White "8) Grivas secondary lines"]
[Black "Grivas, 4.Nxd4 Qb6 5.Nb3 e6 6.a3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Qb6
{ After this move, we have reached the starting position of the Grivas Sicilian. Black's Queen is prematurely developed, hitting the Knight and using the fact that Be3 is not yet possible.   This way, the white Knight will have to move to a rather passive square. Later, the Queen usually drops back to the c7-square. }
5. Nb3
{ This Knight retreat allows us to chase the Queen away from b6 eventually by means of Be3 without having to worry about the b2-pawn.   We'll also have another piece near our King when we castle long. }
5... e6 6. a3
{ This move order is our attempt to transpose back to our line. We also keep the option of playing with c4. }
6... Qc7 7. c4
{ After this move, we'll reach a typical Maroczy setup against the Hedgehog.   However, as the Black Knight is already committed to c6, Black will struggle to get an ideal piece arrangement, which will offer White a comfortable edge. }
7... Nf6 8. Nc3 b6
{ In this position, there are many possible setups, and more than one is correct.   My recommendation is the standard setup with a pawn on f4: this is more powerful against the Knight on c6, as this Knight blocks the b7-Bishop.   Also, the f4-pawn controls the e5-square, so it won't be easy to reroute the Knight in the future. }
9. f4 d6 10. Be2 { Looking for a speedy castle. } 10... Bb7 11. Be3
{ Bringing another piece to the center with more control over the d4 square. }
11... Be7 12. O-O O-O 13. Rc1
{ Next we'll play Qd2 or Bd3+Qf3 with a good space advantage and a nice piece arrangement. }
*

