1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 a6
{ With this move, we enter the O'Kelly Variation. Black's idea is to answer  3.d4  cxd4  Nxd4  Nf6  Nc3  e5  , when it is considered that Black just equalizes. }
3. c4
{ Since Black's 2…a6 didn't fight for the center, we'll use our turn to set up some kind of Maroczy bind.   In general, we'll wait for Black to play …Nc6 before we break on d4, since the Black Knight is usually better placed on d7 in Hedgehog setups. }
3... Nc6
{ Usually this is not an ideal square for the Knight in these structures. } 4.
d4 cxd4 5. Nxd4 Nf6 6. Nc3 e5 7. Nf5 d5
{ An interesting attempt to unbalance the position.   7...d6  8.Ne3 } 8. cxd5
Nxe4
{ An interesting line recently tried by Goryachkina. White should be a bit careful in order to get a nice advantage.  9.Nxg7  is interesting too and likely to give some advantage.   However, the resulting positions are much more comfortable to play for Black. }
9. Ng3 { Retreating and proposing the exchange. } 9... Nxg3 10. hxg3 Nd4 11.
Bd3 { Aiming straight at h7. } 11... Bd6 12. Bd2
{ We go first for our Queenside development to prevent Black's short castle. }
12... Bd7 13. Rc1
