1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 a6
{ With this move, we enter the O'Kelly Variation. Black's idea is to answer  3.d4  cxd4  Nxd4  Nf6  Nc3  e5  , when it is considered that Black just equalizes. }
3. c4
{ Since Black's 2…a6 didn't fight for the center, we'll use our turn to set up some kind of Maroczy bind.   In general, we'll wait for Black to play …Nc6 before we break on d4, since the Black Knight is usually better placed on d7 in Hedgehog setups. }
3... d6 4. d4
{ Here we can't delay d4, since Black was threatening …e5 closing the center.   In any case, Black will get an inferior Hedgehog: due to the early …d6, …Bb4 will never be threatened and White doesn't need to burn a tempo on a3. }
4... cxd4 5. Nxd4 Nf6 6. Nc3 e6
{ The most usual move. Black aims at a Hedgehog setup by a strange move order and we won't let that run smoothly.   6...g6  7.Be2±  would transpose to a Maroczy where Black has wasted a tempo on a6. }
7. Be3 Be7 8. Be2
{ In this order we remain fully flexible: we could castle long or short even and play f4 or g4 if needed. }
8... Qc7 9. g4
{ Out of more than 300 games after …Qc7, White only played g4 in 3 of them. The goal is to gain space and prepare a potential Kingside attack.   Black is not in time to create some decent counterplay. We'll play g5 next and then Qc2 and long castle with a very nice position. }
9... h6 { 9...Nc6  10.g5  Nd7  11.h4+- } 10. h4
{ The attack on the Kingside is coming really fast. } *

