O-O Nxd4 { Some GMs have tried this. However, it is not enough to equalize. }
9. Qxd4 Bd6 10. Kh1 { Typical move to stop …Bxh2 and prepare f4. } 10... O-O
11. f4 e5 12. Qf2 exf4 13. Qh4 h6 14. h3
{ This move is intended to prevent 17…Ng4 in the line with  14.Bxf4?!  Bxf4  15.Rxf4  g5  16.Qxh6  Qxf4  17.Rf1  Ng4??  .   14.h3!!  Re8  Here comes a long sequence that we need not memorizing, but is instructive:  15.Bxf4  Bxf4  16.Rxf4  g5!  17.Qxh6  Qxf4  18.Rf1±  Nxe4  19.Rxf4  Re6  20.Qxe6  Ng3  21.Kh2  dxe6  22.Rd4  Nxe2  23.Rd8  Kg7  24.Nxe2±  . After this extremely long and forced sequence, we reach this endgame which greatly favors us thanks to our Rook on d8. }
*

