5... Nc6 { 6.O-O?!  Nd4!= } 6. d4 { Just in time. } 6... cxd4 7. Nxd4 Nf6 8.
O-O Bb4 { We need to look out for our e4-pawn if Black takes. } 9. Nxc6 bxc6
10. Qd4 { The Queen comes to the center to defend our weak pawn. } 10... e5 11.
Qd3 Bxc3 12. bxc3 c5 13. Bg5
{ The advantage of the Bishop pair, especially the dark-square Bishop, offers us a pleasant game.   A possible continuation is f4, opening up the position. }
