18... b6 19. Ba3 { 19.Be3  is also winning, but somewhat more complicated. }
19... Qxa2 20. Bxc6 { Our Bishops can coordinate for a devastating attack. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "9) O'Kelly"]
[Black "O'Kelly: 2.Nf3 a6 3.c4 e6 4.Nc3 Qc7… 8.O-O Bb4 9.Nxc6 dxc6 #11"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 a6
{ With this move, we enter the O'Kelly Variation. Black's idea is to answer  3.d4  cxd4  Nxd4  Nf6  Nc3  e5  , when it is considered that Black just equalizes. }
3. c4
{ Since Black's 2…a6 didn't fight for the center, we'll use our turn to set up some kind of Maroczy bind.   In general, we'll wait for Black to play …Nc6 before we break on d4, since the Black Knight is usually better placed on d7 in Hedgehog setups. }
3... e6 4. Nc3
{ We are not in a hurry to play d4 as long as Black is not really threatening …e5. }
4... Qc7 5. Be2
{ Black is not threatening neither …e5 nor …Nd4 yet. Therefore, we are not in a hurry to play d4, and then moves such as …Bb4 won't be possible. }
5... Nc6 { 6.O-O?!  Nd4!= } 6. d4 { Just in time. } 6... cxd4 7. Nxd4 Nf6 8.
O-O Bb4 { We need to look out for our e4-pawn if Black takes. } 9. Nxc6 dxc6
{ Out of more than 100 games reaching this position, White only found the best follow-up in 3! }
10. f4
{ We offer the pawn in exchange for the dark squares and the initiative. Not taking the pawn is met by e5 with a huge advantage. }
10... Bxc3 11. bxc3 Qb6+
{ This check is important in order to keep the d4-square under control after …Nxe4. }
12. Kh1 Nxe4
{ Not taking this pawn would mean Black has given up the dark squares for nothing, and again e5 would be on its way. }
13. Bf3
{ The key. We sacrifice an exchange as well as the pawn, but we get a grip on the position and our pieces will be tremendously active. }
13... Nf2+ 14. Rxf2 Qxf2 15. Ba3
{ Black has only developed their queen, which is far from the King. Castling is virtually impossible and White will continue improving their pieces until suffocating their opponent. }
15... Qb6 { Black needed to play this to protect the dark squares. } 16. Rb1
{ Getting yet another piece in play, and with a tempo! } 16... Qa5 17. Qd6
{ Our Bishop and Queen are coordinating dangerously against the Black King. }
17... Qd8 18. Qc5
{ Negating Black's hopes for castling and effectively paralyzing their position. }
*

