{ We insist on our idea of playing with our b5-Knight on c3, to prevent it from being misplaced on a3. Leaving it on b5 until Black plays a6 is good, as developing the Bishop on g7 would leave the d6-pawn hanging. }
7... a6
{ One of the most interesting move orders. Black will recapture on d5 with a Knight instead of using a tempo on …Be6. }
8. N5c3 Nge7
{ With this accurate move order, Black prevents White from placing a Knight on d5 and then recapturing with the other Knight after its trade. }
9. O-O
{ 9.h4!?  is also interesting but unnecessary, as the position gets too messy and this move isn't stronger than the text. }
9... Bg7 10. Bg5
{ Pinning the Knight and trying to provoke some weaknesses by means of …f6 or …h6. }
10... O-O 11. Nd5 f6 12. Be3 Nxd5 13. exd5 Nb8 14. Nc3 f5 15. f3
{ With the typical position we are always seeking. Next, we'll continue with our Queenside counterplay. }
*

