[Black "Kalashnikov 6...Be7 #5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5
{ The Kalashnikov Sicilian is quite similar to the Sveshnikov. The most obvious difference is that here both the b1 and the g8 Knights remain on their starting squares, which entails some changes.   Black has some extra options, like playing …Be7+Bg5 to trade Bishops, pushing …f5 without having to retreat the Knight or even developing this Knight on e7 and the Bishop via …g6+Bg7. Also, the typical Bg5 pin won't be so easy for White.   Obviously, there are some drawbacks as well: since White hasn't been forced to play Nc3, there is the extra option of playing some Maroczy-like setup by means of c4, and that's how we are going to play. }
5. Nb5 d6 6. c4 Be7 7. N5c3
{ Far less known than the absolute main move  7.N1c3  . The key is enjoying more flexibility with our Knights, as we keep the extra option Nd5-Nbc3.   It may look like this move wastes one tempo compared to N1c3.   However, it's very likely that …a6 is going to be played anyway.   Also, as in this position the center is closed, we can comfortably afford this. }
7... Be6
{ The best reply, together with  7...Nf6  . With this move order, Black keeps the option of preparing a timely …Bg5 before developing their g8-Knight. This way the Knight won't burn tempi. }
8. Nd5 Bxd5
{ Both recaptures are sound and offer White some advantage. Personally I'd rather play  9.exd5  , as the resulting position is somewhat more unbalanced.   8...Nf6  9.Bd3  . }
9. cxd5 Nd4 10. Be3 Nf6 11. Nc3
{ First we protect the e4 pawn, then we will just finish our development. } *

