[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "11) Classic Sicilian secondary lines"]
[Black "6...e5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Nc6
{ The Classical Sicilian, certainly one of the trickiest and hard to understand. One of its perks is its flexibility: Black can play ...e5, ...e6, or even ...g6 Dragon-style. Recently it has become more popular and currently, it is one of the most played in open tournaments. }
6. Bc4
{ Again, my recommendation will be somewhat unexpected for our opponents. Most of them will be used to the more usual  6.Bg5  and our idea is basically to look for Be3+Qe2+O-O-O and prepare a kingside attack. }
6... e5
{ This doesn't work well on this move order, as our bishop gives us a good light-square control. }
7. Nf5 Be6
{ Trying to make us help them improve their pawn structure. In case of  8.Bxe6  fxe6  expells our strong Knight from  f5  , fixes the  d5  hole and yields the f-file for Black's Rook after casting. But we keep it simple with }
8. Qd3 { Establishing a strong grip over the light squares. } 8... Nb4
{ The slow approach is no better for Black.  8...Rc8  9.o-o  a6  covering the b5 check  10.Bb3⩲  Again, we have everything ready to control the light squares. }
9. Bb5+ Nd7 10. Qd1
{ 10...a6  11.Ba4±  Intending Bb3 to control the light squares. } 10... d5
{ Relying on the looseness of our f5-Knight but it's never a good idea to open the position relying on tactics, when you are behind in development. }
11. a3 dxe4 12. Nxg7+ Bxg7 13. axb4
{ Leaving Black with a bad structure and not enough safety for the king. } *

