[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "11) Classic Sicilian secondary lines"]
[Black "6...Qb6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Nc6
{ The Classical Sicilian, certainly one of the trickiest and hard to understand. One of its perks is its flexibility: Black can play ...e5, ...e6, or even ...g6 Dragon-style. Recently it has become more popular and currently, it is one of the most played in open tournaments. }
6. Bc4
{ Again, my recommendation will be somewhat unexpected for our opponents. Most of them will be used to the more usual  6.Bg5  and our idea is basically to look for Be3+Qe2+O-O-O and prepare a kingside attack. }
6... Qb6
{ The main alternative to 6...e6, forcing us to do something with the well-positioned d4-Knight and difficulting the c1-Bishop's development.  Black is ready to play the resulting structure after Nxc6 and this is what we are going to do. Initially, I was going to recommend 7.Nb3, but after quite a deep analysis I realized Black is close to equal and it is too big a memory effort just to get a similar or worse position than after 7.Nxc6. }
7. Nxc6
{ The simplest. We reach one of the most typical Sicilian structures when plans will matter more than concrete moves. }
7... bxc6 { 7...Qxc6??  8.Bb5+-  wins the Queen. } 8. O-O e6
{ The old treatment for this variation, blunting our shot at f7. } 9. Qe2
{ Looking for a quick e5 break to provoke another pawn island. } 9... Be7 10.
e5 dxe5 11. Qxe5 O-O 12. b3
{ A nice move securing the c4-Bishop. With b2 covered, we can later decide the best diagonal for our Bishop. We have a comfortable structure, no weaknesses, and a healthy piece play. }
12... Nd5 13. Na4
{ Exchanging pieces is not in our best interest when we have attacking intentions. Neither it is fixing their pawn structure. }
13... Qb8 14. Qh5
{ We play Bb2 and Ra1 next and have a better structure and more active pieces. Against  14...Bf6  we have a nice decision between the slow fire  15.Rb1  with Ba3 and Nc5-e4 ideas, or the more direct  15.Bb2  Bxb2  16.Nxb2  followed by Rae1-Nd3-Ne5 }
*

