1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Nc6
{ The Classical Sicilian, certainly one of the trickiest and hard to understand. One of its perks is its flexibility: Black can play ...e5, ...e6, or even ...g6 Dragon-style. Recently it has become more popular and currently, it is one of the most played in open tournaments. }
6. Bc4
{ Again, my recommendation will be somewhat unexpected for our opponents. Most of them will be used to the more usual  6.Bg5  and our idea is basically to look for Be3+Qe2+O-O-O and prepare a kingside attack. }
6... Bd7
{ One of the most common continuations, preparing Rc8 to accelerate the queenside development and make the c4-Bishop uncomfortable. }
7. Nxc6
{ My main recommendation is 7.Be3  but, since there is a direct transposition to the Dragon, I'll give this alternative line which also offers a comfortable advantage until the second part of this course is available. }
7... bxc6
{ The right square for the Bishop, hitting e4 and leaving d7 for the Knight to jump to e5 or relocate to the queenside. }
8. Bg5 { Normal development, with the quite annoying threat Bxf6+Qh5 } 8... g6
{ 8...e6  9.Qe2⩲  Typical opposite castling race where we are faster.   8...Qa5  9.Bd2  Qc7  10.Qe2±  Looking for O-O-O and the e5 push or a kingside attack.   8...h6  9.Bxf6  gxf6   9...exf6  10.Qh5  g6  11.Qe2⩲  The weakness on d6 piles up on Black's problems.  10.Qh5± }
9. Qf3
{ Very concrete play: O-O-O and e5 come very quickly and Black is not ready yet }
9... Bg7 10. Bxf6 Bxf6 { 10...exf6  11.O-O-O± } 11. e5 dxe5 12. O-O-O
{ Black is paralyzed and the f6-Bishop is suffering. We play Ne4 next with an annoying pin down the d-file. }
*

