1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Nc6
{ The Classical Sicilian, certainly one of the trickiest and hard to understand. One of its perks is its flexibility: Black can play ...e5, ...e6, or even ...g6 Dragon-style. Recently it has become more popular and currently, it is one of the most played in open tournaments. }
6. Bc4
{ Again, my recommendation will be somewhat unexpected for our opponents. Most of them will be used to the more usual  6.Bg5  and our idea is basically to look for Be3+Qe2+O-O-O and prepare a kingside attack. }
6... Bd7
{ One of the most common continuations, preparing Rc8 to accelerate the queenside development and make the c4-Bishop uncomfortable. }
7. Nxc6
{ My main recommendation is  7.Be3  but, since there is a direct transposition to the Dragon, I'll give this alternative line which also offers a comfortable advantage until the second part of this course is available. }
7... Bxc6
{ The right square for the Bishop, hitting e4 and leaving d7 for the Knight to jump to e5 or relocate to the queenside. }
8. Qe2 { Development and defense. } 8... g6
{ The most dynamic development setup. This is where the dark-squared Bishop has a better future.   8...e6  9.Bf4⩲  with intentions of castling queenside to leverage the e5 break. }
9. Bg5 Bg7 10. O-O-O { Setting up e5 ideas. Black should be careful } 10... O-O
{ 10...h6?!  11.Be3  Weakening your castle cannot be good. We simply focus on the g5 break. Black can accelerate their demise with  11...Nxe4  12.Nxe4  Bxe4  13.Bf4!  when nasty things will happen along the d and e files.   10...Qa5  11.h4⩲  again with a typical Yugoslav attack after Kn1-f3-h4 }
11. e5 Qa5
{ The point! Black exploits the bishop is hanging on g5 to avoid losing on the spot. }
12. Bxf6 { 12.exf6??  Qxg5+  13.Kb1  Qxf6∓ } 12... exf6
{ 12...Bh6+  13.Kb1  exf6  14.exd6±  doesn't change anything for Black. } 13.
exd6 { Black must hurry now or their position will soon become very ugly }
13... Rfe8 14. Qd3 Qg5+ 15. Kb1 Qxg2 16. Bd5
{ Eliminating Black's Bishop pair and installing a powerful Knight on d5. The d6-pawn will reach d7 and completely paralyze Black's pieces }
*

