11... Qc7 { The most logical. } 12. e5
{ Surprise! The key idea: we sacrifice a pawn and the bishop pair in exchange for a large initiative and a superior structure. }
12... dxc5 13. exf6 Qf4+
{ 13...Bxf6  14.Ne4  Be7  15.h4±  Black's position has zero counterplay and our pieces occupy excellent squares. We can make progress on both sides of the board with few worries, use g5 for our Knight, the 3rd rank for our Rooks, and toy with h5+h6 ideas. }
14. Kb1 Qxf6 15. Ne4 Qe5 16. Rhe1
{ Again all our pieces are active at the small price of a pawn. The c8-bishop can't even dream of getting active and the Black Queen is still a terget. }
