1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Nc6
{ The Classical Sicilian, certainly one of the trickiest and hard to understand. One of its perks is its flexibility: Black can play ...e5, ...e6, or even ...g6 Dragon-style. Recently it has become more popular and currently, it is one of the most played in open tournaments. }
6. Bc4
{ Again, my recommendation will be somewhat unexpected for our opponents. Most of them will be used to the more usual  6.Bg5  and our idea is basically to look for Be3+Qe2+O-O-O and prepare a kingside attack. }
6... e6 { Once e6 is played, Ng4 is off the cards. Therefore, we start with }
7. Be3 { Finishing development. } 7... a6
{ A common move, preparing b5 at some point while staying flexible regarding development. }
8. Qe2 { Still, we follow our favorite plan. } 8... Na5
{ The knight is pointless on a5 if our bishop can go to d3 } 9. Bd3 b5
{ 9...Be7  10.f4  continuing in typical kingside fashion with g4-g5. } 10. O-O
{ Castling as soon as possible to exploit Black's lack of development by opening up the position. }
10... Qc7 11. Ncxb5
{ Black was posing for the photograph, so we take the shot. Important, it has to be this Knight! }
11... axb5 12. b4
{ The key, forcing the Knight to a miserable square. This is why we needed to sac the c3-Knight. }
12... Nb7 { 13...Nc6  14.Nxc6  Qxc6  15.Bxb5+- } 13. Nxb5
{ With the simple plan of pushing a4+a5+a6 and Na7+b5+b6 at some point. Our Bishop pair controls the entire queenside and Black can do little to oppose our idea as they still have to figure out their development. }
*

