1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Nc6
{ The Classical Sicilian, certainly one of the trickiest and hard to understand. One of its perks is its flexibility: Black can play ...e5, ...e6, or even ...g6 Dragon-style. Recently it has become more popular and currently, it is one of the most played in open tournaments. }
6. Bc4
{ Again, my recommendation will be somewhat unexpected for our opponents. Most of them will be used to the more usual  6.Bg5  and our idea is basically to look for Be3+Qe2+O-O-O and prepare a kingside attack. }
6... e6 { Once e6 is played, Ng4 is off the cards. Therefore, we start with }
7. Be3 { Finishing development. } 7... a6
{ A common move, preparing b5 at some point while staying flexible regarding development. }
8. Qe2 { Still, we follow our favorite plan. } 8... Qc7
{ Control over c4 is key for Black in these positions. } 9. Nxc6
{ Only happened in 2 games, out of more than 1300 reaching this position. }
9... Qxc6 10. Bd3
{ Again, in time to protect e4 and prepare long castle and the kingside push.   10...Be7  11.O-O-O  would be a transposition.   10...Qc7  11.a4  Since we have not yet committed our King,  (compare with this variation.)  we can outright stop Black's main source of counterplay. We can simply castle kingside and play for a queenside clamp with a5. }
10... b5 11. Nxb5 { Again this works due to  11..axb5  12Bxb5+- } 11... Qb7
{ 11...Be7  12.Na7+-  winning the Bishop pair ad keeping an extra pawn for nothing. }
12. Nd4 Nxe4
{ Generally speaking, in middlegames, center pawns are more valuable than wing paws as they have a larger influence in the game.  12...Qxb2  13.O-O±  with a crushing development lead. Our Rooks will use the open file. }
13. Nb3
{ We'll complete our development after O-O. Black's piece coordination is awkward as b7 isn't so natural for the Queen and the  Knight on e4 is a bit lose. Against d5 we have c4 as the opening of the position is to our benefit. }
