[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Nc6
{ The Classical Sicilian, certainly one of the trickiest and hard to understand. One of its perks is its flexibility: Black can play ...e5, ...e6, or even ...g6 Dragon-style. Recently it has become more popular and currently, it is one of the most played in open tournaments. }
6. Bc4
{ Again, my recommendation will be somewhat unexpected for our opponents. Most of them will be used to the more usual  6.Bg5  and our idea is basically to look for Be3+Qe2+O-O-O and prepare a kingside attack. }
6... e6 { Once e6 is played, Ng4 is off the cards. Therefore, we start with }
7. Be3 { Finishing development. } 7... a6
{ A common move, preparing b5 at some point while staying flexible regarding development. }
8. Qe2 { Still, we follow our favorite plan. } 8... Bd7
{ Objectively, Black's best move order. However, a low number of games have seen it. Placing the bishop on d7 is troublesome though, as usually this square is reserved for Black's f6-knight }
9. Bb3 { Improving our bishop and anticipating our opponent's idea. } 9... Na5
{ 10.g4!?  e5  11.g5  exd4  12.Bxd4  is unclear. In practice, it looks uncomfortable to play with Black, but objectively the position is sound. }
10. f4 { This move is usually more powerful after Na5, as e5 is threatened. }
10... Qc7 11. g4
{ The presence of the bishop on d7 is felt, as the f6-knight lacks a good retreat. }
11... b5 12. g5 { Just on time. } 12... b4
{ 12...Ng8  This move is a disaster that should be avoided at all cost  13.f5+- }
13. gxf6 bxc3 14. fxg7 Bxg7 15. O-O-O cxb2+ 16. Kb1
{ After this forcing sequence we reach this complicated position where we have a large advantage. Our king is quite safe thanks to the b3-bishop and b2 is an additional layer of protection. Our pieces are better coordinated thanks to our king being castled, so next, we'll harass the g7-bishop. }
16... Rc8 { Hitting on c2 to limit White's queen. } 17. Rhg1 Bf6
{ The only active square for the Bishop. } 18. Rd2
{ Overprotecting c2 and preparing to double Rooks eventually. } 18... Nxb3 19.
axb3 Qa5 20. Kxb2
{ The rook on h8 is not taking part in the game and we intend to push e5 to take advantage of our activity. }
*

