1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Nc6
{ The Classical Sicilian, certainly one of the trickiest and hard to understand. One of its perks is its flexibility: Black can play ...e5, ...e6, or even ...g6 Dragon-style. Recently it has become more popular and currently, it is one of the most played in open tournaments. }
6. Bc4
{ Again, my recommendation will be somewhat unexpected for our opponents. Most of them will be used to the more usual  6.Bg5  and our idea is basically to look for Be3+Qe2+O-O-O and prepare a kingside attack. }
6... e6 { Once e6 is played, Ng4 is off the cards. Therefore, we start with }
7. Be3 { Finishing development. } 7... a6
{ A common move, preparing b5 at some point while staying flexible regarding development. }
8. Qe2 { Still, we follow our favorite plan. } 8... Bd7
{ Objectively, Black's best move order. However, a low number of games have seen it. Placing the bishop on d7 is troublesome though, as usually this square is reserved for Black's f6-knight }
9. Bb3 { Improving our bishop and anticipating our opponent's idea. } 9... Be7
{ This is inconsistent with the 8...Bd7 move order, which aimed at a quick b5. }
10. O-O-O Qc7
{ 10...O-O-O  11.f4  Qc7  12.g4±  Reaching the typical position, and Black got nothing. }
11. g4 { We are happy to be allowed to play g4 without counterplay } 11... Nxd4
{ The f6-Knight doesn't have many squares so Black needs to make space somehow. }
12. Rxd4 e5
{ 12...Bc6  14.g5  Nd7  14.f4±  with a typical attacking construction. } 13.
Nd5 { 13.Rc4!?  White is clearly better. } 13... Nxd5 14. Rxd5 Bc6 15. g5
{ I really like this positional exchange sacrifice to kill Black's counterplay. If Black accepts it, our light-squared Bishop will be an unopposed monster that will inconvenience the lack King wherever it shelters. Meawhile, Black is left with a big pawn on e7. }
