1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5
{ After this move, we enter the Sveshnikov Sicilian. Black weakens their pawn structure  (hole in d5, backward pawn on d6)  for dynamic assets  (gaining tempo misplacing White's Knight, pawn breaks on d5 and f5, and often times the Bishop pair. In my view, this is objectively the soundest Sicilian, together with the Najdorf.) }
6. Ndb5 d6
{ Virtually the only move. If Black allows Nd6 their position is a disaster. }
7. Nd5
{ Recently this move has become really popular. The  7.Bg5  lines are too studied and White doesn’t seem to get anything out of it. Also, we are aiming again at the same structure we are going to play against other lines. }
7... Nxd5 { Forced. } 8. exd5 Nb8
{ The move we are most likely to encounter on the board. We reach the typical structure in Which Black will seek some counterplay on the kingside, while we do the same on the queenside.  9.c4!?  Reaching similar positions, is the most played. However, a4 has recently become very popular. }
9. a4
{ The point of this early push is to retreat the knight to a3 in case of a6 and eventually play Nc4+a5. }
9... Be7
{ The most flexible move, as e7 is the obvious destination for this bishop and Black is going to castle short. However, other moves like  9...Nd7   9...a6  or  9...f5  are more conditioned by White’s reply. }
10. Bd2
{ The most accurate move order to reach the position we want. Also, it’s not as well-known as  10.Be2  , which its main drawback is  10...Nd7!  This move order has barely been barely played compared to   10...O-O  however, it is more accurate.  11.Bd2   11.O-O  O-O  12.Bd2  a6  13.Na3  a5!  reaches the position our move order is trying to avoid as in my view, Black manages to get the best version of this position.  11...Nf6!  with complicated play. }
10... Nd7
{ A correspondence move but one of the most interesting orders and maybe objectively the best one. Black wants to transpose by meeting  11.Be2  with  11...Nf6! }
11. a5 a6
{ A very concrete attempt against White’s move order. It is quite unnatural, so very unlikely to face on the board unless Black has prepared it in advance. 12.Nc3!?  With the idea of playing Na4+c4 next.   11...Nf6  12.Be3+-  The key difference in this move order. a7 falls. }
12. Na3 Nf6
{ The point. Black is hitting the d5-pawn, as well as threatening a potential Ne4 or Bg4. }
13. Bb4 Bg4 { Very concrete play again, trying to provoke new weaknesses } 14.
f3 Bf5 15. Nc4 Rc8
{ This move, putting indirect pressure on c2, is important to delay Nb6. This is one of the few occasions where I’ll be offering two different lines, as I think this is one of Black’s best replies and it will probably become trendy.   15...O-O  16.Nb6  Rb8  17.Bd3⩲  Finishing development and aiming at castling. In these positions without f5, White is comfortably preparing their plan without much counterplay on Black’s part. }
16. c3
{ Guarding the bishop in order to play Bd3 without any Nxd5 shenanigans, as well as enabling Nb6. }
16... O-O 17. Bd3 e4
{ The key. Black is just in time to liquidate the position towards a slightly worse endgame.   17...Nxd5  18.Bxf5  now b4 is defended.   17...Bxd3  18.Qxd3⩲ }
18. fxe4 Bxe4 19. O-O Rc7
{ Again the most accurate. Black anticipates Nb6.   19...b5  20.Nb6⩲   19...Bxd5?  20.Nb6  Rc7  21.Rxf6+-  Everything collapses. }
20. Bxe4 Nxe4 21. Qe2 Rxc4 22. Qxc4 Nd2 23. Qf4 Nxf1 24. Kxf1
{ All these nuances have led us to this position. Black needs to be even more precise to get full equality. Our pressure on d6, combined with a rook quickly coming to e1, offer us this little plus. }
