{ 17...Nxd5  18.bxa6  Nxb4   18...Bxa6  19.Bd2!  19.axb7  Rxb7  20.a6± } 18.
Nxb5 Nxd5 19. Bd2 Bc6 20. Na3 Rxb2
{ After this sequence we reach a complex position. Thanks to our passer and some good piece coordination we have more than enough compensation for the missing pawn. Here are two sample lines. }
21. Bf3
{ 21.Nc4!?  Rxd2!  It’s not easy for our opponent to assess this move, as the natural Rb8 keeps the exchange   21...Rb8  22.Bf3±   22.Qxd2  Bg5  23.Qd1!  Nf4  24.a6!  Ba8!!   24...Bxg2  25.Bf3±  25.a7∞ }
21... Qd7 22. Nc4 Rb5 23. Rc1
{ Black pieces are tangled in the center and it’s hard to untie the knot. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "13) Sveshnikov 8...Nb8"]
[Black "Sveshnikov: 12...a6 #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5
{ After this move, we enter the Sveshnikov Sicilian. Black weakens their pawn structure  (hole in d5, backward pawn on d6)  for dynamic assets  (gaining tempo misplacing White's Knight, pawn breaks on d5 and f5, and often times the Bishop pair. In my view, this is objectively the soundest Sicilian, together with the Najdorf.) }
6. Ndb5 d6
{ Virtually the only move. If Black allows Nd6 their position is a disaster. }
7. Nd5
{ Recently this move has become really popular. The  7.Bg5  lines are too studied and White doesn’t seem to get anything out of it. Also, we are aiming again at the same structure we are going to play against other lines. }
7... Nxd5 { Forced. } 8. exd5 Nb8
{ The move we are most likely to encounter on the board. We reach the typical structure in Which Black will seek some counterplay on the kingside, while we do the same on the queenside.  9.c4!?  Reaching similar positions, is the most played. However, a4 has recently become very popular. }
9. a4
{ The point of this early push is to retreat the knight to a3 in case of a6 and eventually play Nc4+a5. }
9... Be7
{ The most flexible move, as e7 is the obvious destination for this bishop and Black is going to castle short. However, other moves like  9...Nd7   9...a6  or  9...f5  are more conditioned by White’s reply. }
10. Bd2
{ The most accurate move order to reach the position we want. Also, it’s not as well-known as  10.Be2  , which its main drawback is  10...Nd7!  This move order has barely been barely played compared to   10...O-O  however, it is more accurate.  11.Bd2   11.O-O  O-O  12.Bd2  a6  13.Na3  a5!  reaches the position our move order is trying to avoid as in my view, Black manages to get the best version of this position.  11...Nf6!  with complicated play. }
10... O-O { Not committing to anything in the queenside. } 11. Be2
{ 11.a5  is also interesting, but this order is more flexible. } 11... Nd7 12.
a5
{ With this precise order we reach this position where we have avoided the best version of the a6+a5 line. If nothing else, this will allow us get our opponents out of the book, but also, of course, we avoid Black’s best line }
12... a6 13. Na3 Nf6
{ A very interesting and concrete idea, still untested in over-the-board chess  (so far only in correspondence chess)  . Deep engine analysis indicates Black is very close to equalizing. However, in practical play Black’s position is uncomfortable. }
14. Bb4 { 13.c4?!  13...Ne4!= } 14... b5 15. c4
{ 15.axb6  Bb7  16.Ba5  Bxd5  17.O-O  Bb7  18.c4  We reach a complex position where Black still has something to prove and our b6 pawn is annoying, but I think the text move is more challenging for Black. }
15... Bb7
{ Far more accurate than the direct capture. Now White is forced to take on c4 with the bishop.   15...bxc4?!  16.Nxc4  Bb7  17.Nb6±  This just helps White. }
16. O-O bxc4 17. Bxc4 Rc8 18. b3
{ Reaching a quite complex position: the weakness on a6 is more noticeable than ours on d5, as it is harder to defend. Our next step will be to reroute the a3-knight and centralize our rooks. }
*

