{ corr. Gaining some space and intending to develop the c8-bishop via f5. Again I’ll offer two options for White, as I belive this line will become trendy }
19. c4 { We start our queenside push. } 19... Bf6
{ 19...Qc7  20.Be2±  The queen belongs in the kingside and is not well placed on c7.   19...Nxf3+  20.Qxf3  20.Bf6  21.Bc3± }
20. Kh1 { Sacrificing the pawn to get some activity } 20... Nxf3
{ 20...Bf5  21.c5!⩲ } 21. Qxf3 Bxb2 22. Rae1
{ All our pieces occupy very challenging squares, in striking contrast with our opponent’s. Black will need to be very precise to avoid getting into serious trouble. }
22... Qc7 23. Qb3 Be5 24. c5 f3
{ This leads to a very long and forcing line.   24...Qxc5  25.Rxe5  dxe5  26.d6+  Kh8  27.d7  winning. }
25. c6 { We ignore our castle for the sake of our passer. } 25... Bg4
{ 25...fxg2+  26.Kxg2±  The King is safe. } 26. gxf3 Bh3 27. Rg1 Bd4
{ Black needs to find something concrete to justify their pawn sacrifice and White’s passer. }
28. Rg3 Bf5 29. Rg5 Bg6 { 29...Qf7  30.Bc3± } 30. Rg4
{ The black bishop is left without good squares and Nd7 wins a prize. } 30...
Bf2 { 30...Bf6  31.Nd7± } 31. Re2 Bc5 32. Nd7
{ Great square for the knight... } 32... bxc6 33. Nxb8 Rxb8 34. Qc4
{ We are an exchange up and have a better endgame. } *

