1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5
{ After this move, we fully enter the Sveshnikov/Pelikan Sicilian. In my view, this is objectively the soundest Sicilian, together with the Najdorf. }
6. Ndb5 d6
{ Virtually the only move. If Black allows Nd6 their position is a disaster. }
7. Nd5
{ Recently, this move has become really popular. The Bg5 lines are too studied, and White doesn’t seem to get anything out of it. Also, we are aiming again at the same structure we are going to play against other lines. }
7... Nxd5 8. exd5 Ne7
{ 8...Nb4  9.c3  Na6  10.Be3  The knight is very awkward on a6 and White can go on with normal piece development. }
9. c4 Nf5
{ The oldest line, Quite forgotten in recent years. Logically, having the knight here, any black plan involving f5 is more difficult to execute.   9...a6  This move loses directly and more than 200 players have already fallen for this trap!  10.Qa4  Kd7  11.Bd3  Well, I think this position is self-explanatory. That king on d7 has taken the plunge.   If @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/1p2nppp/p2p4/1N1Pp3/Q1P5/8/PP3PPP/R1B1KB1R b KQkq - 1 10@@EndFEN@@  10...axb5  11.Qxa8  Nf5  12.cxb5  with material advantage and we continue with our development.   If  11...bxc4  12.Bxc4   If @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/1p2nppp/p2p4/1N1Pp3/Q1P5/8/PP3PPP/R1B1KB1R b KQkq - 1 10@@EndFEN@@  10...Bd7  11.Nxd6 }
10. Bd3 Be7
{ The main line. I think Black can’t really make much of their pieces with this setup. }
11. O-O O-O 12. a4
{ As always, aiming at the a5 push. This is not easy to stop: if Black played a5, the b5-square would be weakened for life.   With the knight on f5 we don’t need to worry about the weaknesses on b4 and c5, as there’s no black piece to use them. }
12... Bd7 13. Kh1 { Intending an eventual f4. } 13... a6 14. Nc3
{ Many good plans are possible here, including the a5 push and the f4 break, seeking counterplay on the kingside. }
*

