[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5
{ After this move, we fully enter the Sveshnikov/Pelikan Sicilian. In my view, this is objectively the soundest Sicilian, together with the Najdorf. }
6. Ndb5 d6
{ Virtually the only move. If Black allows Nd6 their position is a disaster. }
7. Nd5
{ Recently, this move has become really popular. The Bg5 lines are too studied, and White doesn’t seem to get anything out of it. Also, we are aiming again at the same structure we are going to play against other lines. }
7... Nxd5 8. exd5 Ne7
{ 8...Nb4  9.c3  Na6  10.Be3  The knight is very awkward on a6 and White can go on with normal piece development. }
9. c4 Ng6
{ Played by Carlsen in many games of the World Championship, after which this became really trendy. }
10. Qa4
{ A very concrete move, trying to stir trouble in Black’s position. Now Bd7 is forced and our queen will be really annoying on b4. }
10... Bd7 11. Qb4 Qb8
{ If  11...Bxb5  12.Qxb5+  Qd7  13.a4  Bishop pair for free and zero counterplay for our opponent. Now the knight is pointless on g6. }
12. h4 { Again intending to bug the knight or provoke some weakening with h5. }
12... h5 13. Be3
{ Threatening c5 and trying to provoke a6 to exploit the weakness on b6 later on.   13.Be2  a6  14.Nc3  Be7  15.g3  b5!!= }
13... a6
{ 13...Be7  14.c5   13...b6  14.O-O-O  Be7  15.Kb1  We reach a position with opposide-side castling where the black pieces struggle to come near our king and we can slowly make some progress. }
14. Nc3 Be7 15. Na4 Qc7
{ 15...Nxh4  16.Nb6  Nf5  17.Bd2  The knight on b6 is very well placed and the missing pawn is not really felt. }
16. g3 Bg4
{ Controlling key light squares and stopping a potential long castle. } 17. Bg2
O-O 18. f3 { Castling and allowing e4+Ne5 is very risky. } 18... Bc8
{ 18...Bd7  19.Nb6  Rab8  20.O-O-O } 19. Nb6 Rb8 20. O-O-O
{ With a very comfortable opposite-side castling position thanks to our powerful knight on b6. }
