[White "14) Sveshnikov 8...Ne7"]
[Black "Sveshnikov 8...Ne7 9.c4 10.Qa4 #10"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5
{ After this move, we fully enter the Sveshnikov/Pelikan Sicilian. In my view, this is objectively the soundest Sicilian, together with the Najdorf. }
6. Ndb5 d6
{ Virtually the only move. If Black allows Nd6 their position is a disaster. }
7. Nd5
{ Recently, this move has become really popular. The Bg5 lines are too studied, and White doesn’t seem to get anything out of it. Also, we are aiming again at the same structure we are going to play against other lines. }
7... Nxd5 8. exd5 Ne7
{ 8...Nb4  9.c3  Na6  10.Be3  The knight is very awkward on a6 and White can go on with normal piece development. }
9. c4 Ng6
{ Played by Carlsen in many games of the World Championship, after which this became really trendy. }
10. Qa4
{ A very concrete move, trying to stir trouble in Black’s position. Now Bd7 is forced and our queen will be really annoying on b4. }
10... Bd7 11. Qb4 Bf5 12. h4
{ We want to bug the knight, as well as enable Bg5 in certain position. If our pawn reaches h5, Black could have long-term problems, since castling with our bishop on e2 is awkward due to the weakness of that h5-pawn. }
12... h5 13. Bg5
{ We use the fact that Be7 is not possible due to the weakness on d6 and that the f6 push creates too many weaknesses. Thus we can send the black queen to a worse square with a tempo. }
13... Qb8 { 13...f6  Too weakening  14.Be3  a6  15.Nc3  Qd7  16.a4  . } 14. Be2
{ We go on with our development and target h5. } 14... a6
{ Black needed to get rid of this knight to be able to continue with some normal development. }
15. Nc3 Qc7 16. g3 Be7 17. Be3 e4
{ Black’s typical plan in this position, to bring their pieces to life. We need to be careful with the light squares.   17...O-O  18.Bxh5  You can see here what I mentioned about the h5-pawn.   17...Nf8  Rerouting the knight to a better square, but this is too time-consuming  18.a4  Nd7  19.a5  . }
18. Qa4+ { 18.Rd1!? } 18... Kf8
{ 18...Bd7  19.Qb3  Bf5  Thanks to this little maneuver our queen is slightly closer to the kingside in case we need her majesty via c2 or d1.  20.O-O  O-O  21.Bxh5  .   If  19...f5  20.O-O-O  Ne5  21.Kb1  O-O  22.Rd2  .  If  21...Rc8  22.c5  . }
19. O-O Ne5 20. Rad1
{ Actively centralizing our rooks. The liberating c5 push is already on the cards. }
20... Bg4 { 20...Re8  21.c5  dxc5  22.Nxe4  Bxe4  23.Qxe4   20...Rd8  21.Rd4 }
21. Bxg4 hxg4 22. Nxe4 Qxc4 23. Qxc4 Nxc4 24. Bf4
{ All our pieces are active and will quickly improve, whereas Black’s army has to wait passively. }
