[Black "7...b5 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6
{ The Najdorf Sicilian, always considered one of the best variations to play with Black. Used by Kasparov and more recently by MVL who has strived day by day at the top level to prove that it holds up @@StartBracket@@I play it too, but nobody cares about that@@EndBracket@@. }
6. Be2
{ I recommend this move because I consider that it has many advantages over the others.   To begin with, it is a seemingly harmless move against which our opponents will not have spent as many hours of study as against other apparently more critical moves, so it is likely that they will not be as well prepared.   The two main answers, as against almost all of White's options on move 6, are 6...e6 and 6...e5.   Usually, Najdorf players tend to have a preference for one structure over the other, but this does not mean that one is better than the other; it is simply a matter of taste. Generally, e6 will lead to more complex games since piece exchanges are more unusual in that structure and plans tend to be more focused on attacks on both flanks. }
6... e5
{ The main move these days. Black gains space in the center and moves our strong Knight away from the center. The game will center around the weak d5-square: they'd love to achieve d6-d5, but for the moment we have a better grip over it. }
7. Nb3 b5
{ Immediately creating problems on e4 and trying to weaken our control over d5. This is a typical move in the Najdorf but we are happy to see Black moving pawns when we have a lead in development. }
8. a4 { Opening the queenside! } 8... b4 9. Nd5
{ 9...Nbd7  10.O-O  Bb7  11.Bd2  b4 is in trouble. We welcome  11...a5  as our Bishop gets b5 to hinder Black's development. Whilst exchanging e4 and b4 results in us having two open lines in the center and full development to punish Black for their queenside skirmish! }
9... Bb7 10. a5 Nbd7
{ 10...Nxd5  11.exd5+-  and the Rook comes to  a4  to take on  b4  .   10...Nxe4?  11.Bf3  f5  12.g4+-  Black's position does not hold. }
11. Ra4
{ Winning the pawn. We have control over the center and the light squares. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "15) Najdorf with 6...e5 and 7...Be6"]
[Black "8...b5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6
{ The Najdorf Sicilian, always considered one of the best variations to play with Black. Used by Kasparov and more recently by MVL who has strived day by day at the top level to prove that it holds up @@StartBracket@@I play it too, but nobody cares about that@@EndBracket@@. }
6. Be2
{ I recommend this move because I consider that it has many advantages over the others.   To begin with, it is a seemingly harmless move against which our opponents will not have spent as many hours of study as against other apparently more critical moves, so it is likely that they will not be as well prepared.   The two main answers, as against almost all of White's options on move 6, are 6...e6 and 6...e5.   Usually, Najdorf players tend to have a preference for one structure over the other, but this does not mean that one is better than the other; it is simply a matter of taste. Generally, e6 will lead to more complex games since piece exchanges are more unusual in that structure and plans tend to be more focused on attacks on both flanks. }
6... e5
{ The main move these days. Black gains space in the center and moves our strong Knight away from the center. The game will center around the weak d5-square: they'd love to achieve d6-d5, but for the moment we have a better grip over it. }
7. Nb3 Be6 { Not so common as  7...Be7  but still a major Najdorf move order. }
8. Be3 b5 9. a4
{ Again, we are better developed so opening the position benefits us. } 9... b4
10. Nd5 Nbd7
{ 10...Bxd5  11.exd5±  is strategical suicide. Black can afford to part with the light-squared bishop only when they have concrete counterplay against d5 or in the kingside. Here, they have none, and the light squares and queenside are chronically weak. }
11. a5
{ Reaching a5 is always a victory, b6 and b4 are weak and we can continue with our development. }
11... Nxe4 12. Bb6
{ 12...Nxb6  13.axb6  condemns the a6-pawn. It says all you need to know that the engine rather prefers to lose the exchange. }
*

