[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6
{ The Najdorf Sicilian, always considered one of the best variations to play with Black. Used by Kasparov and more recently by MVL who has strived day by day at the top level to prove that it holds up @@StartBracket@@I play it too, but nobody cares about that@@EndBracket@@. }
6. Be2
{ I recommend this move because I consider that it has many advantages over the others.   To begin with, it is a seemingly harmless move against which our opponents will not have spent as many hours of study as against other apparently more critical moves, so it is likely that they will not be as well prepared.   The two main answers, as against almost all of White's options on move 6, are 6...e6 and 6...e5.   Usually, Najdorf players tend to have a preference for one structure over the other, but this does not mean that one is better than the other; it is simply a matter of taste. Generally, e6 will lead to more complex games since piece exchanges are more unusual in that structure and plans tend to be more focused on attacks on both flanks. }
6... e5
{ The main move these days. Black gains space in the center and moves our strong Knight away from the center. The game will center around the weak d5-square: they'd love to achieve d6-d5, but for the moment we have a better grip over it. }
7. Nb3 Be6 8. Be3 Nbd7
{ Interesting move order rather little tested. It is not as easy as it seems to transpose to the other line that we want to play because after   9.O-O  Be7  10.Qd3  there is  10...Rc8  and  11.Nd5  is not good because of  11...Bxd5  12.exd5  Nb6  with counterplay against d5.   Obviously, there are other moves but I preferred to recommend something quite concrete against this line. }
9. f4
{ Again we are looking for concrete lines. Black must now decide whether to take on f4 or allow f5. }
9... Rc8
{ Another way to support the Bishop trade on c4. However, the Rook is not as influential in the queenside as the Queen. }
10. f5 Bc4 11. Bxc4 Rxc4 12. Qd3
{ Preparing to castle to take advantage of the d-file. } 12... Qc8
{ 12...Rc8  13.O-O-O  b5  14.a3±  stopping b5-b4 and following with our kingside advance. }
13. Nd2 Rc7 14. O-O-O
{ With an advantage in development. We will play h3 to prepare g4. } *

