{ The king here is very safe. We connect the rooks and control the very important square d3, so that the Black Queen cannot take advantage of it. }
17... Bd6 18. Rab1 { Black's Queen begins to feel a bit claustrophobic. } 18...
Nxd5 19. exd5
{ 19...O-O  20.Qe4±  We will continue with our kingside attack with or without Queens. }
19... Nf6 20. Rhc1 Qa4 21. Rc6
{ The madness begins. Black has to sacrifice the rook to avoid running out of counterplay. }
21... e4 { The best try for counterplay. } 22. Qh1
{ From here the queen has easy access to all areas of the board. } 22... Rd8
{ 22...Kd7  23.Rbc1± } 23. b3 Qxa3 { 23...Qa5  24.Bb6+- } 24. Bd4
{ All our pieces are extremely active and that Queen on a3 is in danger. Black must continue with the concrete line in order not to lose on the spot. }
24... e3 25. Ne4 { 25...O-O  26.Bxf6  gxf6  27.Qc1± } 25... Nxd5
{ The key! Black sacrifices the Rook in exchange for a lot of counterplay. }
26. Nxd6+ Rxd6 27. Rc8+ { 27...Rd8  28.Rxd8+  Kxd8  29.Qxd5+- } 27... Kd7 28.
Rxh8 Qb4 { 28...Qa2+  29.Rb2+- } 29. Qc1
{ Defense and counterattack.     29...Ne7  30.Qxe3+- } 29... Rc6 30. Qd1 Qd6
{ 30...Ke7  31.Kf1  Black must hurry. If our king moves away from the danger, it's all over. }
31. Bxe3 { Moving the Bishop out of the way is important. } 31... Qxh2+
{ 31...Nc3+  32.Ke1  Nxd1  33.Rxd1+-   31...Rc3  32.Bf2+- } 32. Bf2 Qg2
{ 32...Rd6  33.Kf3+- } 33. Rc1 Qe4+
{ 33...Qxg4+  34.Kf1  Qh3+  35.Kg1+-  Black runs out of checks. } 34. Kf1 Qh1+
35. Bg1
{ Taking advantage of the fact that the Knight is pinned and the checks will be over. }
35... Qh3+ 36. Ke1 Qg2 37. Qxd5+ Qxd5 38. Rd1
{ Black has to give up the Rook in order not to lose the Queen. } 38... Rc1 39.
Rxc1 Qe4+ 40. Kd2
{ After this great number of only moves we get to this endgame. Black is going to run out of checks pretty soon and when White coordinates his pieces, Black's king is going to be in trouble. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "15) Najdorf with 6...e5 and 7...Be6"]
[Black "8...Nbd7 and 9...exf4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6
{ The Najdorf Sicilian, always considered one of the best variations to play with Black. Used by Kasparov and more recently by MVL who has strived day by day at the top level to prove that it holds up @@StartBracket@@I play it too, but nobody cares about that@@EndBracket@@. }
6. Be2
{ I recommend this move because I consider that it has many advantages over the others.   To begin with, it is a seemingly harmless move against which our opponents will not have spent as many hours of study as against other apparently more critical moves, so it is likely that they will not be as well prepared.   The two main answers, as against almost all of White's options on move 6, are 6...e6 and 6...e5.   Usually, Najdorf players tend to have a preference for one structure over the other, but this does not mean that one is better than the other; it is simply a matter of taste. Generally, e6 will lead to more complex games since piece exchanges are more unusual in that structure and plans tend to be more focused on attacks on both flanks. }
6... e5
{ The main move these days. Black gains space in the center and moves our strong Knight away from the center. The game will center around the weak d5-square: they'd love to achieve d6-d5, but for the moment we have a better grip over it. }
7. Nb3 Be6 8. Be3 Nbd7
{ Interesting move order rather little tested. It is not as easy as it seems to transpose to the other line that we want to play because after   9.O-O  Be7  10.Qd3  there is  10...Rc8  and  11.Nd5  is not good because of  11...Bxd5  12.exd5  Nb6  with counterplay against d5.   Obviously, there are other moves but I preferred to recommend something quite concrete against this line. }
9. f4
{ Again we are looking for concrete lines. Black must now decide whether to take on f4 or allow f5. }
9... exf4
{ The main move as Black doesn't want to be crushed under the weight of our kingside pawns. }
10. Bxf4 Ne5 11. Qd4 Be7
{ The Knight needs no defense yet. Our King belongs in the queenside and if would not be able to take it there if we took the pawn. }
12. O-O-O O-O 13. Bxe5 dxe5 14. Qxe5
{ Now it is a good moment. We are a healthy pawn up that will be healthier after a well-prepared Nd5. }
14... Nd7 { 14...Qb6  15.Nd5  Bxd5  16.exd5±  and the d5-pawn is too strong. }
15. Qg3
{ With a comfortable material advantage. Our Knights will be brought quickly to the center. }
*

