9. f4
{ Again we are looking for concrete lines. Black must now decide whether to take on f4 or allow f5. }
9... exf4
{ The main move as Black doesn't want to be crushed under the weight of our kingside pawns. }
10. Bxf4 Ne5 11. Qd4 Be7
{ The Knight needs no defense yet. Our King belongs in the queenside and if would not be able to take it there if we took the pawn. }
12. O-O-O Qc7 { Defending e5. } 13. Qa4+
{ A well-timed check to disrupt Black's attention from d5. } 13... Bd7
{ 13...Nc6  14.Nd5± } 14. Bb5
{ An importabt intermezzo, taking advantage of the pin to the Rook. } 14... O-O
15. Bxd7 { 15...Nexd7  16.g4  transposing to  (this line.) } 15... Qxd7 16.
Qxd7 Nfxd7 17. Nd5 Bd8 18. Rhe1
{ All our pieces are playing. The pawn on d6 is weak and the d8-Bishop is very passive. }
*

