[White "16) Najdorf with 6...e5 and 7...Be7"]
[Black "9...Bxd5?! #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6
{ The Najdorf Sicilian, always considered one of the best variations to play with Black. Used by Kasparov and more recently by MVL who has strived day by day at the top level to prove that it holds up @@StartBracket@@I play it too, but nobody cares about that@@EndBracket@@. }
6. Be2
{ I recommend this move because I consider that it has many advantages over the others. To begin with, it is a seemingly harmless move against which our opponent will not have spent as many hours of study as against other apparently more critical moves, so it is likely that he is not as well prepared. The two main answers as against almost all of White's moves on 6 are e6 or e5. Generally Najdorf players tend to have a preference for one structure over the other, but this does not mean that one is better than the other; it is simply a matter of taste. Generally e6 will lead to more complex games since piece exchanges are more unusual in that structure and plans tend to be more focused on attacks on both flanks. }
6... e5 7. Nb3 Be7 8. Be3 Be6 { The correct move order. } 9. Nd5 Bxd5
{ This move is an inaccuracy as white now has extra options such as the move g4 in some positions or developing the queen to d2 instead of d3. }
10. exd5 O-O 11. g4
{ If we prefer quieter positions we can simply fix the queenside with  11.a4  a5  and transpose.   11...h6  12.h4+- }
11... Nbd7 12. h4 Nb6 13. c4 Rc8 14. Nd2 { The Knight will be dominant on e4. }
*

