[White "16) Najdorf with 6...e5 and 7...Be7"]
[Black "9...Nxd5?! 10.exd5 Bf5 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6
{ The Najdorf Sicilian, always considered one of the best variations to play with Black. Used by Kasparov and more recently by MVL who has strived day by day at the top level to prove that it holds up @@StartBracket@@I play it too, but nobody cares about that@@EndBracket@@. }
6. Be2
{ I recommend this move because I consider that it has many advantages over the others. To begin with, it is a seemingly harmless move against which our opponent will not have spent as many hours of study as against other apparently more critical moves, so it is likely that he is not as well prepared. The two main answers as against almost all of White's moves on 6 are e6 or e5. Generally Najdorf players tend to have a preference for one structure over the other, but this does not mean that one is better than the other; it is simply a matter of taste. Generally e6 will lead to more complex games since piece exchanges are more unusual in that structure and plans tend to be more focused on attacks on both flanks. }
6... e5 7. Nb3 Be7 8. Be3 Be6 { The correct move order. } 9. Nd5 Nxd5 10. exd5
Bf5 11. Qd2
{ Threatening things with Na5, avoiding Bg5 and giving us the possibility to castle long. }
11... O-O
{ 12.Na5  also has a lot of interest but I think black suffers less.  12...Qc7  13.O-O  Bg6!  and now it seems that the best try is  14.Qc3  and, although we are slightly better, I think that Black holds well. }
12. O-O
{ Finishing development. It also has the great advantage that the seemingly most normal move of the position  12...Nd7  is a mistake.  13.Na5!  Now it will not be possible to kick this knight away with b6 since c6 will be weakened.  13...Qc7  14.c4±  with advantage in the queenside race. }
12... Bg6 13. a4
{ Does this plan sound familiar to you? Once again it is again very interesting and we reach positions with themes that we will master. }
13... Nd7 { 13...a5  14.Bb5±  Again, this is familiar. } 14. a5
{ Getting to the desired structure. } 14... Rc8
{ 14...f5  15.f4!  As almost always we avoid Black's f4, now also with the advantage of leaving the Bishop inactive on g6.  15...Nf6  16.Rad1⩲  we can follow with 17.Qb4. }
15. c4
{ 15...Re8  16.Rae1⩲  With the typical healthy middlegame that we are looking for. }
15... f5 16. f4 { Stay there on f5, please! } 16... Bf6 17. fxe5 Bxe5
{ 17...Nxe5  18.Nd4±  accessing the weaknesses. } 18. Bf4
{ With the bishop on g6 this structure is worse for Black since e6 is weaker and the g5 plan is not available. }
*

