14... g6 { Keeping all ideas flexible. } 15. Kh1 Ne8
{ The same idea as always but with the kingside a little more blocked. I recommend two quite concrete options for White.   15...Re8  16.Qd1  Rerouting the knight with Nd2, which is a slightly more comfortable position for White. The weaknesses on the light squares created by Black on the queenside will remain latent. }
16. Qd2
{ Hoping to put Black in a crossroads. We will meet b6 more often, probably, after which having the Queen on d2 is very important in many lines because it has been removed from the jumps to c5 and e5. }
16... b6 17. Bh6 Ng7 18. f4 a4 19. Na1
{ This is the ideal square to be able to get to c6. } 19... Bf6 { Allowing f5 }
20. f5 Nxf5
{ In case of allowing g4 also on the next move Black will hardly be able to move anymore.   20...gxf5  21.g3±  stopping f4 and bringing the Knight to e3. }
21. Bxf8 Kxf8 22. Bg4
{ Very concrete, it is dangerous to let Black reorganize because the lack of open files means that the rooks are not worth so much at the moment. }
22... Bh4
{ There are two good options here and it depends a bit on which position we prefer to play.   23.Bxf5  Bxe1  24.Qh6+  The bishop can wait.  24...Kg8  25.Bxd7  Qxd7  26.Rxe1  Rxc4  27.b3±  Although the knight is now badly placed, as soon as it enters the game Black will be in so much trouble. }
23. Re2 Qg5 24. Bxf5 Qxd2 25. Rxd2 gxf5 26. Rxf5 Rxc4 27. Nc2
{ The exchange up will be noticeable as time goes by. We continue now with g3-Kg2. }
*

