1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6
{ The Najdorf Sicilian, always considered one of the best variations to play with Black. Used by Kasparov and more recently by MVL who has strived day by day at the top level to prove that it holds up @@StartBracket@@I play it too, but nobody cares about that@@EndBracket@@. }
6. Be2
{ I recommend this move because I consider that it has many advantages over the others. To begin with, it is a seemingly harmless move against which our opponent will not have spent as many hours of study as against other apparently more critical moves, so it is likely that he is not as well prepared. The two main answers as against almost all of White's moves on 6 are e6 or e5. Generally Najdorf players tend to have a preference for one structure over the other, but this does not mean that one is better than the other; it is simply a matter of taste. Generally e6 will lead to more complex games since piece exchanges are more unusual in that structure and plans tend to be more focused on attacks on both flanks. }
6... e5 7. Nb3 Be7 8. Be3 Be6 { The correct move order. } 9. Nd5 Nbd7
{ The correct order, as it is the most flexible for Black and forces the move Qd3. }
10. Qd3
{ We develop the queen, defend the e4 pawn and control the f5 square, avoiding Nxd5+Bf5. }
10... Bxd5
{ Again, this just makes things easier for us by giving us more options. } 11.
exd5 Rc8
{ Be careful with this move. Black controls c4 and Nb6 becomes a threat. Giving the Bishop for the Knight on b6 is not an option, so we have to look for an alternative. }
12. c4 O-O 13. O-O a5
{ One of the best lines against this 6.Be2-setup. From my point of view, it requires extensive knowledge of the Najdorf by Black as it is far from the usual treatment of these positions. Black seeks to close the queenside by continuing with b6 and take things very calmly on the kingside. }
14. Rae1
{ We change our mindset completely and we focus on preparing f4.   14...a4  15.Nd2  Nc5  16.Qc2⩲  Black has no need to play so much on the queenside. We follow with b4. }
14... g6 { Keeping all ideas flexible. } 15. Kh1 Ne8
{ The same idea as always but with the kingside a little more blocked. I recommend two quite concrete options for White.   15...Re8  16.Qd1  Rerouting the knight with Nd2, which is a slightly more comfortable position for White. The weaknesses on the light squares created by Black on the queenside will remain latent. }
16. f4 { THe most direct, hoping for f5. } 16... f5
{ 16...a4  17.Nd2  f5  18.Qa3⩲  (Putting pressure on the weakness which is close to fall.)   16...b6  17.f5±   16...exf4  17.Bxf4⩲ }
17. fxe5 dxe5 18. d6
{ Opening absolutely everything to take advantage of our bishops and Black's weakened king. }
18... Bxd6 19. c5 Be7 { 19...Nxc5  20.Nxc5+- } 20. Rc1
{ Preparing Qb5 or Rfd1, with total domination. } 20... a4 21. Na5 {  } *

