16... Qd7 { Seeking the light suqares. } 17. a4 a5
{ In this line, Black will basically try to close everything and hold on to an opposite colorbishop endgame with a pawn down or some other disadvantage. }
18. Bg5 { Hoping to follow up with Rae1+Bd1 and fight for the e4-pawn. } 18...
Be5 { Trying to avoid the pawns becoming doubled. } 19. Rae1 Qf5 20. Be3
{ The Queen on f5 is undefended and this allows things like f4. } 20... Rfe8
{ 20...b6  21.f4  Bd4  22.Bd1⩲  This is the structure we are looking for now, where our plan will be to prepare g4 with Qg2. }
21. f3 Bd4
{ 21...Qh3  22.f4!  Bd4  23.Bd1⩲  Qf2 forces the exchange and the Qg2 helps push g4. }
22. Bd1 Qe5 23. f4 Bxe3+ 24. Rxe3 Qd4 25. Re1 { Again, the plan is to go g4. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "16) Najdorf with 6...e5 and 7...Be7"]
[Black "11...Bxd5 12.exd5 Nc5!? #5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6
{ The Najdorf Sicilian, always considered one of the best variations to play with Black. Used by Kasparov and more recently by MVL who has strived day by day at the top level to prove that it holds up @@StartBracket@@I play it too, but nobody cares about that@@EndBracket@@. }
6. Be2
{ I recommend this move because I consider that it has many advantages over the others. To begin with, it is a seemingly harmless move against which our opponent will not have spent as many hours of study as against other apparently more critical moves, so it is likely that he is not as well prepared. The two main answers as against almost all of White's moves on 6 are e6 or e5. Generally Najdorf players tend to have a preference for one structure over the other, but this does not mean that one is better than the other; it is simply a matter of taste. Generally e6 will lead to more complex games since piece exchanges are more unusual in that structure and plans tend to be more focused on attacks on both flanks. }
6... e5 7. Nb3 Be7 8. Be3 Be6 { The correct move order. } 9. Nd5 Nbd7
{ The correct order, as it is the most flexible for Black and forces the move Qd3. }
10. Qd3
{ We develop the queen, defend the e4 pawn and control the f5 square, avoiding Nxd5+Bf5. }
10... O-O 11. O-O Bxd5 12. exd5 Nc5
{ It has lost a lot of popularity, it is not the typical Najdorf structure but it is still very interesting. Thanks to the protected passed pawn and the bishop pair we keep a more comfortable position, but we have to be precise. }
13. Nxc5 dxc5
{ The line with more games follows with  14.Bf3  However, after a lot of analysis, I ended up concluding that Black equalizes very comfortably after  14...Bd6  15.Bg5  h6  16.Bh4  b5  17.b3  c4! }
14. c4 e4
{ Risky move. The pawn on e4 becomes a target, so be careful with the plan Nd7+f5. }
15. Qc2 { The point! Now we focus on that weaknesses with Rfe1-Bf1-g3 ideas. }
15... Bd6 16. g3
{ Fighting against the d6-Bishop.   16...Qc7  17.Bg5  Be5  18.Rfe1  Following Bf1, after which the e4-pawn will end up falling.   16...Re8  17.a4  a5   17...Nd7  18.Bg4!   17...Qd7  18.a5!⩲  18.Rfe1  Qd7  19.Bd2  h5  20.Bf1!⩲  We continue putting pressure with Bg2. }
16... Qd7 { Seeking the light suqares. } 17. a4 a5
{ In this line, Black will basically try to close everything and hold on to an opposite colorbishop endgame with a pawn down or some other disadvantage. }
18. Bg5 { Hoping to follow up with Rae1+Bd1 and fight for the e4-pawn. } 18...
Rfe8 19. Rae1 { We will only take on c6 at the precise moment. } 19... Qh3
{ 19...Be5  20.Bd1  We will end up gaining the e4 pawn in exchange for the column or, in case black retakes on b2, we will have the b-file, the passed pawn and a very comfortable position.   19.Qf5  20.f4⩲  taking advantage of the pin. }
20. Bd1 Ng4 21. Bxg4 Qxg4 22. Bf4 Bxf4 23. Rxe4
{ Reaching an endgame with a comfortable advantage thanks to our protected passed pawn. }
*

