[White "16) Najdorf with 6...e5 and 7...Be7"]
[Black "12...Ne8 #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6
{ The Najdorf Sicilian, always considered one of the best variations to play with Black. Used by Kasparov and more recently by MVL who has strived day by day at the top level to prove that it holds up @@StartBracket@@I play it too, but nobody cares about that@@EndBracket@@. }
6. Be2
{ I recommend this move because I consider that it has many advantages over the others. To begin with, it is a seemingly harmless move against which our opponent will not have spent as many hours of study as against other apparently more critical moves, so it is likely that he is not as well prepared. The two main answers as against almost all of White's moves on 6 are e6 or e5. Generally Najdorf players tend to have a preference for one structure over the other, but this does not mean that one is better than the other; it is simply a matter of taste. Generally e6 will lead to more complex games since piece exchanges are more unusual in that structure and plans tend to be more focused on attacks on both flanks. }
6... e5 7. Nb3 Be7 8. Be3 Be6 { The correct move order. } 9. Nd5 Nbd7
{ The correct order, as it is the most flexible for Black and forces the move Qd3. }
10. Qd3
{ We develop the queen, defend the e4 pawn and control the f5 square, avoiding Nxd5+Bf5. }
10... O-O 11. O-O Bxd5 12. exd5 Ne8
{ The most common move,played by the Najdorf expert, MVL. Black is looking for f5 and Bg5 ideas. }
13. a4
{ Looking for our usual structure with a5, used by Carlsen and also played in hundreds of correspondence games. }
13... Bg5 14. a5
{ We are in no hurry to take on g5 as this would improve Black's Queen. We will continue with c4 and Black will run out of useful moves. }
14... Rc8 15. c4
{ The pawn here is perfectly positioned because of the e2-bishop, so we don't have to worry about it. }
15... g6
{ Black is waiting for us to remove the Knight from b3 to be able to play f5 and, after f4, our Knight will not have such easy access to d4. However, our moves have been more useful than theirs and we get there first. }
16. Nd2 f5 17. Bxg5 Qxg5 18. Rad1
{ Same idea as before, we defend the Knight to free up the Queen. } 18... e4
{ 18...Nef6  19.Qa3  Ne8  20.b4±  Same plan as always. we are hoping for c5. }
19. Qa3 Ne5
{ 19...Qe7  20.b4⩲  The type of position we are looking for. We will bring the Bishop quickly to f1 to delay Black's attack and we gradually prepare c5. }
20. f4 exf3 21. Nxf3 Nxf3+ 22. Rxf3
{ The knight on e8 is a pain and we have several very annoying plans such as Rb3+b6 or the typical b4+c5 pushes. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "17) Najdorf with 6...e6"]
[Black "Najdorf, 6...e6 7.f4 Qc7 & 8...b5?! #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6
{ The Najdorf Sicilian, always considered one of the best variations to play with Black. Used by Kasparov and more recently by MVL who has strived day by day at the top level to prove that it holds up  (I play it too, but nobody cares about that)  . }
6. Be2
{ I recommend this move because I consider that it has many advantages over the others.   To begin with, it is a seemingly harmless move against which our opponent will not have spent as many hours of study as against other apparently more critical moves, so it is likely that he is not as well prepared.   The two main answers as against almost all of White's moves on 6 are  6...e6  or  6...e5  .   Generally, Najdorf players tend to have a preference for one structure over the other, but this does not mean that one is better than the other; it is simply a matter of taste. Generally e6 will lead to more complex games since piece exchanges are more unusual in that structure and plans tend to be more focused on attacks on both flanks. }
6... e6
{ Normally, e6 players will be happy to be able to play this way against our Be2 since White usually continues with O-O without looking for anything particularly ambitious, but we are going to surprise them by looking for very direct lines with f4+g4+g5 following with a potential long castle. }
7. f4
{ The most precise move order. We gain some space and keep all the options flexible.   7...Nbd7  8.Bf3  Qc7  9.a4  Black does not get any kind of counterplay with this move order. }
7... Qc7
{ The general idea of this move is going for a quick counterplay on the queenside with b5, trying to save a tempo not playing Be7 in order to be a bit faster. }
8. g4 { But we are faster! } 8... b5
{ This is not the best continuation. However, we can probably see this move the most in our games. }
9. g5
{ Taking the knight out of f6 has many advantages. To begin with, the e4 pawn will suffer less, Black's development will be more unnatural and the f5 advance will gain in strength since the e5 reply will not always be possible due to Nd5 ideas. }
9... Nfd7 10. a3
{ Prophylaxis against b4. Without the knight on f6 and this push prevented, the e4 pawn will no longer be a problem. }
10... Nc6 11. Rf1
{ We prepare f5 without exposing ourselves to the jumps on c4. } 11... Be7
{ 11...Bb7  12.f5+- } 12. Be3
{ Preparing to castle Queenside and carry on the pawn storm. } *

