{ Normally, e6 players will be happy to be able to play this way against our Be2 since White usually continues with O-O without looking for anything particularly ambitious, but we are going to surprise them by looking for very direct lines with f4+g4+g5 following with a potential long castle. }
7. f4
{ The most precise move order. We gain some space and keep all the options flexible.   7...Nbd7  8.Bf3  Qc7  9.a4  Black does not get any kind of counterplay with this move order. }
7... Be7 8. Be3
{ We continue our development keeping the option of g4 and O-O-O ideas. } 8...
O-O 9. g4 { Let's go! } 9... d5
{ Once again this reaction is necessary because the positions after g5 + a3 is very good.   9...Nc6  10.g5  Nd7  11.h4  .   9...b5  10.g5  Nfd7  11.a3  Just in time, and once again we arrived at our ideal formation with a nice advantage. }
10. e5 Nfd7 11. g5
{ We avoid Bh4, which is more flexible than h4 since we have the possibility of a rook lift through the 3rd rank to attack. }
11... Nc6 { 11...b5  12.Bd3 } 12. Bd3
{ The most direct one aiming at h7. Black has to be extremely precise if he doesn't want to lose almost on the spot. The threat is Nxe6 followed by Bxh7 + Qh5 + g6.   12.h4  is also interesting looking to play a little more calmly and also gives a certain advantage. }
12... Qb6
{ Practically the only move. 13.Rb1 to continue with Cce2 looking for calmer lines is also possible. However, Black can continue sacrificing on e5 to complicate and objectively Na4 is a bit stronger. }
13. Na4 Qa5+ 14. c3 Nxd4 15. Bxd4 b5 { Did we blunder a piece? } 16. Nb6 Nxb6
17. Bxh7+ { We 'blunder' another one for the sake of it. } 17... Kxh7 18. Qh5+
Kg8 19. O-O
{ Black's extra material is of little use to him if his pieces do not participate in the defense. It follows Rf3-Rh3 and mate will be unstoppable. }
*

