{ One of the advantages of attacking the castled king with two bishops is that if our opponent manages to block one of them, the other will have more potential, as it happens in this case. }
20. b3 Na3
{ Another piece that is doomed to be far away from the King. We do not care about the Bishop on c2 anymore because the fight will take place on the dark squares now. }
21. Nb6 Bh3
{ I have already warned that there were more bad natural moves and this is another example. }
22. b4 Qb5 23. Bd3 Nc4 24. Qe1 { Winning. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "17) Najdorf with 6...e6"]
[Black "Najdorf, 6...e6 7.f4 Be7 … 17.Bf2 e5 #7"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6
{ The Najdorf Sicilian, always considered one of the best variations to play with Black. Used by Kasparov and more recently by MVL who has strived day by day at the top level to prove that it holds up  (I play it too, but nobody cares about that)  . }
6. Be2
{ I recommend this move because I consider that it has many advantages over the others.   To begin with, it is a seemingly harmless move against which our opponent will not have spent as many hours of study as against other apparently more critical moves, so it is likely that he is not as well prepared.   The two main answers as against almost all of White's moves on 6 are  6...e6  or  6...e5  .   Generally, Najdorf players tend to have a preference for one structure over the other, but this does not mean that one is better than the other; it is simply a matter of taste. Generally e6 will lead to more complex games since piece exchanges are more unusual in that structure and plans tend to be more focused on attacks on both flanks. }
6... e6
{ Normally, e6 players will be happy to be able to play this way against our Be2 since White usually continues with O-O without looking for anything particularly ambitious, but we are going to surprise them by looking for very direct lines with f4+g4+g5 following with a potential long castle. }
7. f4
{ The most precise move order. We gain some space and keep all the options flexible.   7...Nbd7  8.Bf3  Qc7  9.a4  Black does not get any kind of counterplay with this move order. }
7... Be7 8. Be3
{ We continue our development keeping the option of g4 and O-O-O ideas. } 8...
O-O 9. g4 { Let's go! } 9... d5
{ Once again this reaction is necessary because the positions after g5 + a3 is very good.   9...Nc6  10.g5  Nd7  11.h4  .   9...b5  10.g5  Nfd7  11.a3  Just in time, and once again we arrived at our ideal formation with a nice advantage. }
10. e5 Nfd7 11. g5
{ We avoid Bh4, which is more flexible than h4 since we have the possibility of a rook lift through the 3rd rank to attack. }
11... Nc6 { 11...b5  12.Bd3 } 12. Bd3
{ The most direct one aiming at h7. Black has to be extremely precise if he doesn't want to lose almost on the spot. The threat is Nxe6 followed by Bxh7 + Qh5 + g6.   12.h4  is also interesting looking to play a little more calmly and also gives a certain advantage. }
12... Qb6
{ Practically the only move. 13.Rb1 to continue with Cce2 looking for calmer lines is also possible. However, Black can continue sacrificing on e5 to complicate and objectively Na4 is a bit stronger. }
13. Na4 Qa5+ 14. c3 Ndxe5 15. fxe5 Nxe5 16. Bc2
{ Logically, black has compensation thanks to the central pawns, White's king and the knight misplaced on a4. However, he still has to be precise enough to avoid getting lost and the position will still be objectively better for White. }
16... Nc4
{ 17.Qd3  also gives some advantage, but I consider the textual stronger and more difficult for our opponent to find the best moves. }
17. Bf2 { Keeping the pair of bishops and our attacking ideas alive. } 17... e5
18. O-O { We give back the piece, but our forces will be very active. } 18...
exd4 19. Bxd4 g6
{ One of the advantages of attacking the castled king with two bishops is that if our opponent manages to block one of them, the other will have more potential, as it happens in this case. }
20. b3 Na3
{ Another piece that is doomed to be far away from the King. We do not care about the Bishop on c2 anymore because the fight will take place on the dark squares now. }
21. Nb6 Bh3
{ I have already warned that there were more bad natural moves and this is another example. }
22. b4 Qb5 23. Bd3 Qc6 24. Re1 Rae8 { 24...Be6  25.Nxa8  . } 25. Rxe7
{ After this sac, all the dark squares remain devastated. } 25... Rxe7 26. Qf3
Bf5 27. Nxd5 Re6 28. Bxf5 gxf5 29. Qxf5
{ With a complete domination of the position thanks to our pieces. } *

