{ Switching to a Dragon with a6 and Be2 included. This is a worse version of it, as the plans with b5 in the Dragon are usually not good. However, the bishop on e2 supports the future f3 pawn and the g4 advance in many lines.   6...b5?  Black is not developed enough to justify this.  7.Nd5  Very concrete, trying to exchange Black's only developed piece and hoping to open the position with a4 or c4.  7...Nxe4??  8.Bf3  Extreme lack of development = Catastrophe.  8...f5  9.Qe2  .  If  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/4pppp/p2p4/1p1N4/3Nn3/5B2/PPP2PPP/R1BQK2R b KQkq - 1 8@@EndFEN@@  8...Nc5  9.O-O  .  If  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/4pppp/p2p1n2/1p1N4/3NP3/8/PPP1BPPP/R1BQK2R b KQkq - 1 7@@EndFEN@@  7...e5  8.Nxf6+  Qxf6  9.Nf5  The light squares are very weak.   If  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/4pppp/p2p1n2/1p1N4/3NP3/8/PPP1BPPP/R1BQK2R b KQkq - 1 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Nxd5  8.exd5  Bb7  9.c4  .  If  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/4pppp/p2p1n2/1p1N4/3NP3/8/PPP1BPPP/R1BQK2R b KQkq - 1 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Nbd7  Watch out!  8.Nc6  .  If  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/4pppp/p2p1n2/1p1N4/3NP3/8/PPP1BPPP/R1BQK2R b KQkq - 1 7@@EndFEN@@  7...e6  8.Nxf6+  Qxf6  9.Be3  c4 or a4 will follow, opening the position to take advantage of our development.   6...Nc6  7.Be3  e6  8.f4  Be7 }
7. Be3
{ Far from castling short, as our opponent may expect, what we will do is to play in the most aggressive way, taking advantage that the bishop controls g4 and we will skip f3 in some lines, making our attack faster. }
7... Bg7 8. Qd2 { Preparing long castle. } 8... O-O 9. O-O-O b5 10. h4
{ Our expansion starts. } 10... Bb7 { 10...h5  11.a3 } 11. Bf3 Nbd7
{ 11...b4  12.Nd5  We control the center. } 12. e5 dxe5 13. Nc6
{ Black loses material. } 13... Qe8
{ 13...Bxc6  14.Bxc6  It is hard to suggest a move for Black. } 14. Nxe7+ Qxe7
15. Bxb7 Nb6 { 15...Rab8  16.Bxa6 } 16. Bxa8 Nc4 17. Nd5 Nxd5 18. Qxd5 Qb4 19.
Rde1 { White is up a full rook, and the king can run to the kingside safely. }
*

