1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6
{ The Najdorf Sicilian, always considered one of the best variations to play with Black. Used by Kasparov and more recently by MVL who has strived day by day at the top level to prove that it holds up @@StartBracket@@I play it too, but nobody cares about that@@EndBracket@@. }
6. Be2
{ I recommend this move because I consider that it has many advantages over the others.   To begin with, it is a seemingly harmless move against which our opponent will not have spent as many hours of study as against other apparently more critical moves, so it is likely that he is not as well prepared.   The two main answers as against almost all of White's moves on 6 are  6...e6  or  6...e5  .   Generally Najdorf players tend to have a preference for one structure over the other, but this does not mean that one is better than the other; it is simply a matter of taste. Generally e6 will lead to more complex games since piece exchanges are more unusual in that structure and plans tend to be more focused on attacks on both flanks. }
6... Nbd7
{ This is a similar line to e6 because the pawn will end up there in most cases. The idea is to confuse our opponent with the move order. }
7. Be3 e6 8. g4
{ Again, our idea in this structure is connected with this push. } 8... h6 9.
f4 g5
{ The key to Black's idea, his play will have the e5-square as its epicenter. }
10. f5
{ Taking on g5 is another decent option. However, this move puts Black under so much more pressure. }
10... Ne5 11. fxe6 { The most concrete.   11.a3!? } 11... fxe6
{ 11...Bxe6  12.Nf5 } 12. Nf3
{ Black has some options available here, but the evaluation does not change too much. We are going to get a pretty fast castling and hit with h4, taking advantage of the weak King on e8. }
12... Nf7
{ The best move. From here, the knight covers the most important squares. } 13.
h4 gxh4 14. Qd2
{ After breaking Black's solidity, we proceed to castle and take advantage of the king on e8. }
14... Nxg4 15. Bd4 Nfe5
{ 15...Rg8  16.O-O-O  Pawns are more than compensated for development and initiative. }
16. O-O-O Nxf3 17. Bxf3 e5 18. Bg1
{ Black's doubled and isolated h pawns are a weakness more than an advantage, White is better in this position. }
